The question of action is irrelevant to what we are talking about and isn’t an answer because that is our link, fucking dumbass.&#xD;
Catherine Frances Botha.  Professor of Philosophy at the University of Pretoria, South Africa.  “Heidegger, Technology and Ecology,” South Africa Journal, Philosophy.  Volume 22.  No. 2.  2003.  Accessed from: http://www.ajol.info/index.php/sajpem/article/viewFile/31367/23340.  Pg. 157 – M.E.&#xD;
This article investigates Heidegger&amp;#39;s views on technology, specifically focusing on whether it is possible to fit Heidegger&amp;#39;s ideas into an ecologically minded framework. The author concludes that the question of what we should do in the wake of the technological crisis we face is inappropriate in terms of Heidegger&amp;#39;s philosophy, since he proposes that we should first tackle the question “What should we think?”. The question whether Heidegger&amp;#39;s ideas on technology provide us with new paths of action, specifically in terms of ecological practice, is flawed.&#xD;
