&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)The paradox of Abstraction is that(%%) __by &amp;#34;liberating&amp;#34; the object from the constraints of figure to return it to the pure play of form, it chained the object__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)down(%%) __to a hidden structure, a stricter, more radical objectivity than the objectivity of resemblance. It strove to tear off the mask of resemblance__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)and figure in order(%%) __to reach the analytical truth of the object. Under the auspices of Abstraction, we paradoxically moved towards__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)even more reality, towards an unveiling of the &amp;#34;elementary structures&amp;#34; of objectality, in other words towards(%%) __something more real than real__.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
            (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)Reciprocally,(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background: yellow&amp;#34; %)__art has invested the entire realm of reality under the auspices of a general aesthetization__(%%).&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
            (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)At the end of this history, the banality of art is mixed up with the banality of the real world-Duchamp&amp;#39;s gesture, with the automatic transfer of the object, was the inaugural (and ironic) act. The transfer of all reality into aesthetics has become one of the dimensions of general exchange ..(%%).&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
            (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow&amp;#34; %)__All of this in the name of a__(%%)__ simultaneous (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow&amp;#34; %)liberation of art and the real world(%%)__.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
            (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)In fact, this &amp;#34;liberation&amp;#34; consisted in indexing one on the other-a deadly chiasmus for both art and the real world(%%).&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
            (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)The transfer of art has become a useless function in the now integral reality because reality has absorbed everything that negated, transcended or transfigured it. Impossible exchange of this Integral Reality for anything else-it can only be exchanged with itself: repeating itself to infinity(%%).&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
            (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)What could miraculously reassure us about the essence of art today?(%%) __Art is simply what is discussed in the art world, in the artistic community that frantically stares at itself. Even the &amp;#34;creative&amp;#34; act replicates itself to become nothing more than the sign of its own operation-the true subject of a painter is no longer what__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)he or(%%) __she paints but the very fact that__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)he or(%%) __she paints. The painter paints the fact that__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)he or(%%) __she paints. In that way, at least, the idea of art is saved__.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
            (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)This is only one aspect of the conspiracy(%%).&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
            (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)The other aspect is the viewer who, most of the time, does not understand anything, and consumes his or her own culture twice removed. The viewer literally consumes the fact that he or she does not understand it and that it has no necessity to it other than the cultural imperative of belonging to the integrated circuit of culture. But culture itself is only an epiphenomenon of global circulation(%%).&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
            (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)The idea of(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background: yellow&amp;#34; %)__art has become rarified__(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)and minimal(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background: yellow&amp;#34; %)__even in conceptual art, where art ends in the non-exhibition of non-works in non-galleries__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)-the apotheosis of art as a non-event.(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background: yellow&amp;#34; %)__Reciprocally, the consumer moves through it all to test__(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)his or(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background: yellow&amp;#34; %)__her non-enjoyment of the works__(%%).&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
            (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)Taking this conceptual and minimalist logic to the extreme, art could do no better than to disappear without any further discussion. At that point, it would no doubt become what it is: a false problem; every aesthetic theory would be a false solution. Yes, but here is the point:(%%) __it is all the more necessary to talk about art now that there is nothing to say about it__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %). Paradoxically,(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background: yellow&amp;#34; %)__the movement to democratize art only reinforced the privilege of the idea of art, culminating in the banal tautology &amp;#34;art is art.&amp;#34;__(%%)__ Everything can supposedly be summed up in this circular definition__.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
            (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)Marshall McLuhan: (% style=&amp;#34;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;background: yellow&amp;#34; %)&amp;#34;__We have now become aware of the possibility of arranging the entire human environment as a work of art__(%%).&amp;#34;&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
            __The revolutionary idea of contemporary art was that (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow&amp;#34; %)any object(%%), any detail or fragment__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)of the material world(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background: yellow&amp;#34; %)__could exercise the same strange attraction and ask the same__(%%)__ insoluble (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow&amp;#34; %)questions as those formerly reserved for a few rare aristocratic forms called art works(%%)__.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
            (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow&amp;#34; %)__That was its true democracy, not in allowing everyone access to aesthetic pleasure but in__(%%)__ the transaesthetic advent of (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow&amp;#34; %)a world in which each object without distinction would have its fifteen minutes of fame(%%)__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)(especially objects without distinction).(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow&amp;#34; %)__Everyone is equal, everything is great__(%%).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %) The upshot came in the transformation of art and the work itself into an object, without illusion or transcendence, a purely conceptual acting out, generating deconstructed objects that deconstruct us in turn(%%).&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
            __No more faces, no glances, no human figures or bodies there-organs without bodies, flows, molecules, fractals__.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %) The relationship to the &amp;#34;work&amp;#34; is on the level of contamination or contagion: you plug in, become, absorb, immerse yourself just like in flows or networks. Metonymical linkage, chain reactions(%%).&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
            (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow&amp;#34; %)__No more real objects__(%%)__ at all: (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow&amp;#34; %)with readymades, the object is no longer there, only the idea of the object. And we no longer take pleasure in art, only in the idea of art(%%)__.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %) We are deep in ideology(%%).&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;mso-line-height-alt: 10.0pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
            __The readymade holds the double curse of__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)modern and(%%) __contemporary art__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %): the curse of(%%) __immersion in reality and banality along with__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)the curse of conceptual(%%) __absorption in the idea of art__.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %) &#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %) &#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %) &#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)The problem is that if everything is art, then nothing is art. If everything is beautiful, then nothing is beautiful. We are robbed of all sign posts, and plunged into a world of total indifference.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %) &#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)Fernando 2012(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt&amp;#34; %)(Jeremy, Jean Baudrillard Fellow, Media and Communicationsurl:http://egs.academia.edu/Departments/Media_and_Communications(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %) at the European Graduate School, Writing Death, printed by lightning source, milton keynes in an endless edition (version 110606). ISBN 978-90-817091-0-1)&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
 &#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %)And it is not as if doing so comes without a price:(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow&amp;#34; %)__once something is completely calculable, it is also completely exchangeable, completely transparent__(%%).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %) Here, we might momentarily tune in to Jean Baudrillard and attend to his warning that total transparency is the point where(%%) __&amp;#34;(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow&amp;#34; %)every(%%) individual (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow&amp;#34; %)category is subject to contamination, substitution is possible between any sphere(%%) and any other: (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow&amp;#34; %)there is total confusion of types:&amp;#39; Thus, &amp;#34;each category is general- ised to the greatest possible extent, so that it eventually loses all specificity and is reabsorbed by all the other categories. When everything is political, nothing is political(%%) anymore, the word itself is meaningless. When everything is sexual, nothing is sexual anymore, and sex loses its determinants. (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow&amp;#34; %)When everything is aesthetic, nothing is beautiful or ugly anymore, and art itself disappears(%%)__.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %) This paradoxical state of affairs ... is simultaneously the complete actualisation of an idea, the perfect realisation of the whole tendency of modernity, and the negation of the idea and that tendency,(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow&amp;#34; %)__their annihilation by virtue of their very success__(%%),(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt&amp;#34; %) by virtue of their extension beyond their own bounds ... :&amp;#39;12 In order(%%) __for any response to be possible, there have to be boundaries, borders, limits__. (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %)For, without the separation, the space, one would not be able to even begin communicating with another; everything would just be the same. In other words,(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow&amp;#34; %)__what has to be maintained is an exteriority__(%%),(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %) a finitude to all gestures of knowing. This also means that all responding, all response, is always already finite. If this were so, a question remains with us: what of the situation in which the call was made? The trouble is: if one can never be sure what the call even is, when, or even where, it came from-if one is blind to both the source and the object of the call-one is attempting to respond to a complete unknown, an absolute unknowability. However, even though there is no possibility of verification, one is still responding-this suggests that there is still a measure of exchange that is taking place. Whether this exchange can be measured is yet another question; one that perhaps can never be addressed. And since there is an exchange that takes place in spite of the fact that the exchange may be impossible, this suggests that the exchange is a symbolic exchangeritualistic, formal, nothing more-and nothing less-than a form; where the form of the exchange is everything-and in which each individual component is meaningless except for its role within the ritual itself. And(%%) __it is this that Georges Bataille speaks of when he describes (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow&amp;#34; %)a general economy: everything has its role in relation with every other thing, but it has no inherent meaning(%%)__.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %) Thus, it is the significance of the object and not its signification that is of interest.(%%) __This is why__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %)in Bataille&amp;#39;s conception,(%%) __sacrifice plays such a crucial role, where the &amp;#34;essence is to consume profitlessly__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %).. : this is where each exchange is beyond rationality, beyond calculability, beyond reason itself; &amp;#34;unsubordinated to the &amp;#39;real&amp;#39; order and oc~~upied only with the presenf&amp;#39;14 Bataille continues: &amp;#34;sacrifice destroys that which it consecrates. It does not have to destroy as fire does; only the tie that connected the offering to the world of profitable activity is severed, but this separation has the sense of a definitive consumption; the consecrated offering cannot be restored to the real order:&amp;#39;15 Since there is no need for a physical change in the object of sacrifice-&amp;#34;it does not have to destroy as fire does&amp;#34; -this suggests that the tie that is severed is ruptured symbolically. And here, we can re-open the earlier register of trans-substantiation when we consider sacrifice: the form remains the same; in fact there is no perceivable change-this is the point at which all phenomenology fails-but there is always already a difference, an absolute separation from the &amp;#34;real order;&amp;#39; from logic, calculability, reason. The object 85 of sacrifice, &amp;#34;the victim, is a surplus taken from the mass of useful wealth ... Once chosen, he is the accursed share, destined for violent consumption. But the curse tears him away from the order of things ... &amp;#34;16 And it is this tearing away from the order of things-the order of rationalitythat &amp;#34;restores to the sacred world that which servile use has degraded, rendered profane:&amp;#39;17 For, only when it is no longer useful, when it is no longer abstracted-subjected, subsumed under-merely a use~~value, can the object be an object as such, can a subject be a subject as such; a singularity. It is perhaps ironic that only within a general economy is singularity preserved. However, one must remember that the object-or subject-of the sacrifice is never calculated; its worth is never in question, nor even taken into account. In fact, it is never so much who or what is sacrificed, but the fact that there is a sacrifice. We find in The Accursed Share many tales of sacrifice and in each of them there is a sense of reversibility. For instance, in Aztec wars, all deaths were seen as a sacrifice to the gods: if victorious, the Aztecs would sacrifice the prisoners; however, &amp;#34;if the warrior had himself been overcome instead of returning a victor, his death on the field of battle would have had the same meaning as the ritual sacrifice of his prisoner: it would have satisfied the hungry gods:&amp;#39; 111 It is this reversibility that can also be found in the tale of Abraham and Isaac. 1 ~~ When Abraham brings Isaac up to Mount Moriah as a sacrifice to the Lord, he is asked by Isaac, &amp;#34; ... where is the lamb for the sacrifice?&amp;#34; His answer is, &amp;#34;God himself will provide one:&amp;#39; Unknown to Abraham at the time, his response (if one can call it a response at all for it was an empty statement; it was neither a truth nor a lie to Isaac),21 ) is precisely what occurs: it is God who provides the object for the holocaust-the ram that is burnt in Isaac&amp;#39;s place. At the point, in the moment, he raises his knife to sacrifice Isaac, Abraham has already killed him-this is the sacrifice that God required: it is an objectless sacrifice; the act of killing Isaac is the sacrifice; this is the kind of sacrifice that &amp;#34;does not have to destroy as fire does:&amp;#39; It does not matter whether Isaac, or the ram, dies: in either case it &amp;#34;would have satisfied the hungry gods:&amp;#39; The sacrifice itself is a ritual, is purely formal; the exact object-whether it is a warrior or the prisoner-is irrelevant.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %) &#xD;
&#xD;
==== Banality is the only impact in the round; it is the worst possible thing that can happen. ====&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)Baudrillard 11(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %) jean. Yeah, he’s still writing books. Telemorphosis, read it its hilarious. Tell all your friends&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)The twentieth century has seen all sorts(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)¶(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) of crimes(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) - Auschwitz, Hiroshima, genocides(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) - (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)but the lone true perfect crime,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) is,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) according to Heideggerian terms, &amp;#34;the(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) second fall of man, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)the fall into banality&amp;#34;.(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:lime;mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)¶(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) There is a murderous violence of banality(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:lime;mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)¶(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) that(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %), precisely due to its indifference(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) and its monotony, (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)is the subtlest form~~(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) of extermination.(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)A(%%) veritable (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)theatre(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:lime;mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) of cruelty(%%), of our cruelty to ourselves,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)completely played down and without a(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) trace of blood(%%). A perfect crime in that (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)it(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) abolishes all stakes and erases its own(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) (%%)45(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) traces(%%) - but above all in so far as in this(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) murder, we are both the murderers and(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) the victims.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) As long as this distinction(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) exists, the crime is not perfect. And yet in(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) all historical crimes that we know of, the(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) distinction is clear. It is only with suicide(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) that the murderer and the victim become(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) the same, and in this regard the immersion(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) into (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)banality is indeed the equivalent(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) of the suicide of the species.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) The other aspect of this murderous banality(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(%%) is that(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) it erases the theatre of operations(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) of the crime(%%) - it is (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)from then on(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:lime;mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso