(% class=&amp;#34;MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:0in;mso-add-space:auto; mso-line-height-alt:10.0pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;3CardTag&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt&amp;#34; %)__Baudrillard &amp;#39;06__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %) (The Melodrama of Difference (Or, The Revenge of the Colonized), International Journal of Baudrillard Studies, (% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)http:~~/~~/www.ubishops.ca/baudrillardstudies/vol3_1/baudrillard2.htmurl:http://www.ubishops.ca/baudrillardstudies/vol3_1/baudrillard2.htm(%%))&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:0in;mso-add-space:auto; line-height:10.0pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)“(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)We may assume”, wrote Victor Segalen, “that fundamental(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)__ differences will never resolve themselves__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)into a truly seamless and unpatched fabric; increas­ing unity, falling barriers and great (% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;background:yellow&amp;#34; %)__reductions in__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)real (% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; background:yellow&amp;#34; %)__distance__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)must of themselves(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; background: yellow&amp;#34; %)__compensate__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %) somewhere__ __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; background:yellow&amp;#34; %)__by__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)__ means of __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; background: yellow&amp;#34; %)__new partitions__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %) and unantici­pated gaps.”&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:0in;mso-add-space:auto; mso-line-height-alt:10.0pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;background:yellow&amp;#34; %)__Racism is one such “new partition”__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)__. An abreaction to the psychodrama of difference: a response to the phantasy of – and obsession with – becoming “other.” __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; background: yellow&amp;#34; %)__A way out of the psychodrama of perpetual introjection and rejection of the other__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)__. So intolerable is this introjection of differences, in fact, that the other must be exorcized at all costs by making the differences materially manifest__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %). The biological claims of racism are without foundation but, by making the racial reference clear, racism does reveal the logical temptation at the heart of every structural system: the temptation to fetishize difference. But differential systems can never achieve equilibrium: differences oscillate con­stantly between absolute highs and absolute lows.(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; background: yellow&amp;#34; %)__When it comes to the management of otherness__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)__ and difference, the idea of a well-tempered __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; background: yellow&amp;#34; %)__balance is__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)__ strictly __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; background: yellow&amp;#34; %)__utopian__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)__.__&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:0in;mso-add-space:auto; line-height:10.0pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)Inasmuch as(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; background: yellow&amp;#34; %)__the humanist__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;background:yellow&amp;#34; %)__ logic __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; background:yellow&amp;#34; %)__of difference__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)is in some sense a universal simulation (one which culminates in the absurdity of a “right to difference”), it (% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; background:yellow&amp;#34; %)__leads directly__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %), for all its benevolence, (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12.0pt;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; background:yellow&amp;#34; %)__to__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %) that other desperate hallucination of difference known as(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; background: yellow&amp;#34; %)__racism. As differences__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)and the cult of differences(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %) __continue to __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; background: yellow&amp;#34; %)__grow, another, unprecedented kind of violence__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %), anomalous and(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %) __inaccessible to critical rationality, __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; background: yellow&amp;#34; %)__grows__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)__ even faster__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %). Segalen’s (% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)“__unanticipated gaps” are not simply new differences: what springs up__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)in order to combat the total homoge­nization of the world is the Alien – monstrous metaphor for(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; background: yellow&amp;#34; %)__the corpse-like, viral Other: the compound form of all the varieties of otherness done to death by our system__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)__.__&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:0in;mso-add-space:auto; mso-line-height-alt:10.0pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;background:yellow&amp;#34; %)__This is a racism which__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)__,__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %) for lack of any biological underpinning, seizes on the very slightest variations in the order of signs; a racism which quickly(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; background: yellow&amp;#34; %)__takes on a viral and automatic character__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)__, and perpetuates itself__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)while reveling in a generalized semiotics. And(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; background: yellow&amp;#34; %)__this racism can never be countered by any humanism of difference__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)__, for the simple reason that it is itself the virus of difference.__&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoListParagraphCxSpLast&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:0in;mso-add-space:auto; mso-line-height-alt:10.0pt;mso-pagination:none;text-autospace:ideograph-numeric&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-fareast-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;background:yellow&amp;#34; %)__Sermonizing on__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)the internalization of the other and __the __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12.0pt;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;background:yellow&amp;#34; %)__introjection of differences can never resolve the problem of the monstrous forms of otherness, because these forms are the product__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt; font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)__, precisely, __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-fareast-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; background: yellow&amp;#34; %)__of this selfsame obsessional differentiation__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-fareast-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %), this selfsame obsessional__ dialectic of ego and other__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-fareast-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %). Herein lies the whole weakness of those “dialectical” theories of otherness which aspire to promote the proper use of difference. For if racism in its viral, immanent, current and definitive form proves anything, it is that(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt;font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-fareast-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)__ there is no such thing as the proper use of difference__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt; font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %). </headline></objectSummary><objectSummary><link rel="http://www.xwiki.org/rel/object" href="http://opencaselist.paperlessdebate.com/xwiki/rest/wikis/opencaselist/spaces/Texas-San%20Antonio/pages/nerison-stroud%20Neg/objects/Admin.EntryClass/10"/><link rel="http://www.xwiki.org/rel/properties" href="http://opencaselist.paperlessdebate.com/xwiki/rest/wikis/opencaselist/spaces/Texas-San%20Antonio/pages/nerison-stroud%20Neg/objects/Admin.EntryClass/10/properties"/><id>opencaselist:Texas-San Antonio.nerison-stroud Neg:6d19eaeb-6799-42d0-abcd-a13bf54d28fb</id><guid>6d19eaeb-6799-42d0-abcd-a13bf54d28fb</guid><pageId>opencaselist:Texas-San Antonio.nerison-stroud Neg</pageId><wiki>opencaselist</wiki><space>Texas-San Antonio</space><pageName>nerison-stroud Neg</pageName><className>Admin.EntryClass</className><number>10</number><headline>==== Aesthetic beauty cannot be found in modern wind turbines because they are devices and not things and therefore separate us from energy production itself.  Even if we attempted to find that beauty or were technically educated in the machinery of the device, the search would be blocked from the outset by their very character. ====&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)Brittain.  2001.  Their author.  Gordon G. Brittain Jr., “Wind, energy, landscape: reconciling nature and technology,” Geography and Philosophy, Vol. 4, 2001 – M.E.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)We need to become clearer about the character of contemporary technology. No one has done more to clarify it, in my view, than Albert Borgmann.23 Borgmann begins with a distinction between “devices” (those characteristic inventions of our age, among which the pocket calculator, the CD sound system, and the jet plane might be taken as exemplary) and what Heidegger calls “things” (not only natural objects, but human artifacts such as the traditional windmills of Holland). (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)The pattern of contemporary technology is the device paradigm,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) which is to say that technology has to do with “devices” as against “things.”(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Things “engage” us,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) an engagement which is (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)at once bodily, social, and demands skill. (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)A device,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) by way of contrast, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)disengages and disburdens us. It makes no demands on skill,(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) and is in this sense disburdening.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) It is (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)defined in functional terms,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) i.e., (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)a device(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) is anything that (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)serves a(%%) certain (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)human-determined function.(%%) This largely involves the procurement of a commodity.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) That is, a device is a means to procure some human end. Since the end may be obtained in a variety of ways, i.e., since a variety of devices are functionally equivalent, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)a device has no intrinsic features.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)But (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)a device(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) also (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)“conceals,” and(%%) in the process (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)disengages.(%%) The way in which (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)the device(%%) obtains its ends (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)is(%%) literally (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)hidden from view.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) The more advanced the device, the more hidden from view it is, sheathed in plastic, stainless steel, or titanium. Moreover, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)concealment and disburdening go hand in hand. (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)The concealment of the machinery,(%%) the fact that it is distanced from us, (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)insures that it makes no demands on our faculties. The device is socially disburdening(%%) as well (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)in its isolation and impersonality.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)To make the analysis of “devices” more precise, an objection to it should be considered. “Is not ... the concealment of the machinery and the lack of engagement with our world,” Borgmann asks, “due to widespread scientific, economic, and technical illiteracy?”24 That is, why in principle can we not “go into” contemporary devices, “break through” their apparent concealments? Why should we not promote electrical engineering, for example, as a general course of study, and in the process come to know if not also to love contemporary technology?(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Borgmann initially answers this objection along three main lines.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)First, many (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)devices(%%),(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) e.g., the pocket calculator, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)are(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) in principle (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)irreparable(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %); they are designed to be thrown away when they fail.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) In this case, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)there is no point in “going into” the device.(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶ (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)Second, many (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)devices(%%),(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) e.g., the CD sound system, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)are(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) in principle (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)carefree(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %); they are designed so as not to need repair. It is not necessary to go into such devices.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶ (%%)Third, many (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)devices(%%),(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) e.g., the jet plane, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)are(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) in fact (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)s(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)o complex that it is not really possible for anyone but a team of experts to go into them.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Increasingly, this is true of older technologies as well, e.g., automobiles, where “fixing” has become tantamount to “replacing” their various computerized components.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Borgmann contends that (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)even if technical education made much of the machinery of devices perspicuous, two differences between devices and “things” would remain.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)Our engagement with (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)devices would remain(%%) “entirely (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)cerebral” since they resist “appropriation through care(%%), repair, the exercise of skill, (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)and(%%) bodily (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)engagement.”(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Moreover, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)the(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) machinery of a (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)device is anonymous.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) It does not express its creator, “it does not reveal a region and its particular orientation within nature and culture.”25 On both counts, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)devices remain unfamiliar, distanced and distancing.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Typing these words, looking at the monitor on which they appear, I have no real relation to the process or to the machinery involved, no context in which to place them, no knowledge of their origins or of their development. The only thing that really matters is the product.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) We could summarize Borgmann’s position by referring to the familiar theoretical notion of a “black box.” In a “black box” commodity-producing machinery is concealed insofar as it is both hidden from view or shielded (literally), and conceptually opaque or incomprehensible (figuratively). Moreover, just those properties that Borgmann attributes to devices can be attributed equally well to “black boxes.” It is not possible to get inside them, since they are both sealed and opaque. It is not necessary to get inside them either, since in principle it is always possible to replace the three-termed function that includes input, “black box,” and output, with a two-termed function that links input to output directly. All we really care about is that manipulation of the former alters the latter.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Borgmann’s interpretation of technology and the character of contemporary life can be criticized in a number of different ways.26 Still, (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)//the distinction between “things” and “devices” reveals,//(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) I think, (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)//the essence of our inability to develop a landscape aesthetic on which contemporary wind turbines are or might be beautiful,//(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) and(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) thereby (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)explains the widespread resistance to placing them where they might be seen.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %)27 For the fact of the matter is that contemporary (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)wind turbines are for most of us merely devices. (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)//There is therefore no way to go beyond or beneath their conventionally uncomfortable appearance to the discovery of a latent mechanical or organic or what-have-you beauty. The attempt to do so is blocked from the outset by the character of the machine.//(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)28&#xD;
&#xD;
==== Windmills are standardized no matter where they are produced or where they are installed.  This makes them devices completely cut off from the societal evolution of other types of buildings.  This is the real reason for their rejection, not a standard of beauty.  Their device like standardization forecloses the possibility of finding a new sense of beauty in them. ====&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)Brittain.  2001.  Their author.  Gordon G. Brittain Jr., “Wind, energy, landscape: reconciling nature and technology,” Geography and Philosophy, Vol. 4, 2001 – M.E.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)It is interesting to note in this respect how unlike other architectural arrivals on the horizon, such as houses (and traditional windmills), contemporary wind turbines are. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Different styles of architecture developed in different parts of the world in response to(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) local (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)geological and climatic conditions(%%),(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) to the availability of local materials, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)to the (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)spiritual and philosophical patterns(%%) of the local culture.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) As a result, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)these buildings (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)create a context.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) In Heidegger’s wonderful, dark expression, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)they “gather.” But there is nothing “local” or “gathering” about contemporary wind turbines; they are everywhere and anonymously the same,(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) whether produced in Denmark or Japan,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) placed in India or Spain, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)alien objects impressed on a region and in no deeper way connected to it.(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) They have nothing to say to us, nothing to express, no “inside;” (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)they “conceal” rather than “reveal.” The(%%) sense of (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)place that they might(%%) eventually (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)engender cannot(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) not, therefore, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)be unique.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) In this regard, the German landscape architect Christophe Schwann seems to catch just the right note:(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Elements of technical civilization are very often standardized in their outfit. The more of them are placed into landscape, the less is the landmark effect. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Because of standardization, wind generators can be very annoying in the marshes:(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) formerly people could distinguish every church tower telling the name of the place. Today, wherever you look you always see the turning triblades. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)The inflation of standardized elements(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) like high tension masts and wind generators puts down orientation and (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)contributes to(%%) the (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)landscape standardization caused by industrial agriculture.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)30(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) The other comment I want to make about Thayer’s position is this. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Wind turbines are(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) quintessential (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)“devices”(%%) in that (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)they preclude engagement.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Or rather, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)the only way in which the vast majority of people can engage with them is visually(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (and occasionally by ear). (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)They cannot climb over and around them, they cannot get inside them, they cannot tinker with them.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)31 (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)They cannot even get close to them.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) There is no larger and non-trivial physical or biological way in which they can be appropriated or their beauty grasped. The irony, of course, is that (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)//precluded from any other sort of engagement with wind turbines, most people find them visually objectionable,//(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) however they might be willing to countenance their existence as the lesser of evils.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)So, in summary, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)there is not an immediately available aesthetic norm on which wind turbines are “landscape-beautiful,”(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) i.e., (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)there is not an immediately available and adequate conception of “landscape” on which they “fit in.”(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Furthermore, (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)//the “device- like” character of wind turbines forecloses the possibility that on a deeper analysis some new and more generous aesthetic norm might be developed.//(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) For in a straightforward sense these turbines are all “surface.”&#xD;
&#xD;
==== Wind turbines do not have a historical connection with the environment that they are in.  It is due to their uniform nature that they cannot be included into the modern environment.  This has less to do with beauty than it does their evolutionary character.  Even if they can one day be included, they first need to develop a connection to the places that they are in. ====&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)Brittain.  2001.  Their author.  Gordon G. Brittain Jr., “Wind, energy, landscape: reconciling nature and technology,” Geography and Philosophy, Vol. 4, 2001 – M.E.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)Think about it for a moment: (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Except for the blades, virtually everything is shielded,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) including the towers of many turbines, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)hidden from view behind the same sort of stainless steel that sheathes many electronic devices.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Moreover, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)the machinery is located(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) a great distance (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)away from anyone,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) save the mechanic who must first don climbing gear to access it and often, for liability reasons, behind chain-link fences and locked gates.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)The lack of disclosure goes together with the fact that the (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)turbines are merely producers of a commodity,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) electrical energy, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)and interchangeable(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) in this respect (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)with any other technology that produces the same commodity at least as cheaply and reliably.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) The only important differences between wind turbines and other energy-generating technologies are not intrinsic to what might be called their “design philosophies.” That is, while they differ with respect to their inputs, their “fuels,” and with respect to their environmental impacts, the same sort of description can be given of each. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)There is(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %), as a result, but (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)a single standard on the basis of which wind turbines are to be evaluated, efficiency.(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) It is not to be wondered that they are, with only small modifications between them, so uniform.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)Many astute commentators would seem to disagree with this judgment. Thus, for example, Robert Thayer in Gray World, Green Heart, 274:(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) But wind energy’s visibility can also be seen as an advantage if functional transparency is valued. With wind energy plants, “what you see is what you get.” When the wind blows, turbines spin and energy is generated. When the wind doesn’t blow, the turbines are idle. This rather direct expression of function serves to reinforce wind energy’s sense of landscape appropriateness, clarity, and comprehensibility. In the long run, wind energy will contribute to a unique sense of place.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) In fact, however, Thayer reinforces the device-like character of wind turbines. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Only their function is transparent, wind in/electrical energy out;(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) the “black box” (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)where all the processing takes place remains unopened.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) This is roughly the same kind of “comprehensibility” that is involved when we note the correlation between punching numbers into our pocket calculators, hitting an operation key, and seeing the result as a digital read-out.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) There are two more things to be said about Thayer’s position. One is that (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)nothing can be “appropriate” to landscape per se;(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) everything depends on the type of object and the type of landscape, at least if we think of landscapes, following Leopold, in something like biological terms, in terms of integration and compensation. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)It is a matter of context. But as is typical of “devices” generally, (% style=&amp;#34;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)contemporary wind turbines are context-free;(%%) they do not relate in any specific way to the area in which they are placed(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (typically by someone who does not live in the area).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) In particular, Leopold insists on the fact that the (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)appropriateness of objects in landscapes has to do with their respective histories,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) the ways in which they evolved, or failed to evolve, together. But (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)contemporary wind turbines have only a very brief history, and in terms of their basic design parameters(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %)—low solidity, high r.p.m., low torque— (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)differ importantly from the windmills whose history goes back at least 1300 years.(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) If wind turbines have any sort of context, it is by way of their blades and the development of airplanes,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) but (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)it is difficult to see how airplanes fit as appropriate objects or symbols into a windswept and uninhabited landscape.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Of course, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)“in the long run” wind turbines will contribute to a sense of place, but not simply in virtue of having been installed somewhere in massive arrays. (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)//They will first have to acquire particular histories.//(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %)29&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
 &#xD;
&#xD;
==== We are winning three external impacts.  1.) The standardization of windmills means that they have to be financed by large-scale corporations that have no incentive to keep up with them.  This allows for environmental degradation.  2.) The standardization of the wind turbine destroys the character of the community itself which allows for its destruction.  3.) The standardization of wind itself turns it into standing reserve which allows for environmental exploitation.  Only the counterplan can solve the impacts the aff has identified. ====&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)Brittain.  2001.  Their author.  Gordon G. Brittain Jr., “Wind, energy, landscape: reconciling nature and technology,” Geography and Philosophy, Vol. 4, 2001 – M.E.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)At least so far as the American experience is concerned, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)the sheer complexity of (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)contemporary wind turbines(%%) entails that they (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)must be grouped in(%%) rather (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)large arrays, so that installation, maintenance, and repair costs can be minimized. This entails(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %), in turn, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)that they be owned and operated by large companies.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Like other energy-generating technologies, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)their(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) immediate (% style=&amp;#34;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)context is “industrial.”(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) But (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)this fact is problematic(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) for a variety of reasons.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) To begin with, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)the(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) immense (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)size(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) of the arrays standard in the United State (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)is visually objectionable.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Typically, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)they(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) so completely (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)dominate the horizon(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) that (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)it is difficult to integrate them in(%%) any sort of way (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)with their landscape,(%%) even in a rather distant perspective.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)Furthermore, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)the fact that these arrays are owned and operated by large companies,(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) whose bankers and boards of directors live and work far away from the site, (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)diminishes any sense of local connection and,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) more importantly, of (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)local (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)responsibility and control(%%).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)32 (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)Those who make the decisions regarding wind farms are not the same people who must live with them on a daily basis.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) It is a lesson we in this country have been slow to learn, but those “on the ground,” who have a sense of the bounds of both tradition and environment, in general make the best land-use decisions. E.F. Schumacher put it strongly, but in large perspective accurately, when he wrote that(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) It is ... obvious that (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)men organized in small units will take better care of their land or other natural resources than anonymous companies or megalomanic governments which pretend to themselves that the whole universe is their legitimate quarry.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %)33(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) There are two points to be emphasized in this regard. One is that (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)wind energy can grow out of local communities,(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) in which case the turbines are for the most part sited, owned, and operated by local residents, (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)or they can be imposed “from outside,”(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) so to speak. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)In the former(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) case, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)it begins to have that sort of “organic” connection to the whole which characterizes(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Leopold’s notion of (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)“natural beauty.”(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) In the same way, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)it begins to express the life of the people who live there, as something they have freely chosen.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)34(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)The question of local control,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) as of individual comprehension, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)is(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) thus (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)tied(%%) closely (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)to aesthetic appreciation. (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)//What we cannot understand or control might be sublime, but it can never, for the same reason, be beautiful.//(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) There is always and necessarily the question of scale.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)The other point to be emphasized is that (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)local communities tend to have some sort of biological basis.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)35 They are defined at least in part by the plant and animal life of the region, the kind and quality of the soil, the available rainfall and adjacent watersheds. It is sometimes put by saying that (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)communities are characterized not simply in abstract terms,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) in terms of mutual trust and a willingness to sacrifice for the common good, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)but also in terms of “place” and “history.” (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)//To the extent that standardized machines are plunked down in a standardized way, then no matter who owns them, the local character of the community is thereby weakened if not also destroyed,//(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) and with it the possibility of feeling “at home” in it.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) To feel oneself at home in the world, we first have to orient ourselves with respect to it, and this involves being able to recognize and distinguish between things.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) As just indicated, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)these “places”(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) are often identified with an individual terrain and a particular watershed.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) But (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)they (% style=&amp;#34;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)could(%%) just as well (% style=&amp;#34;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)be identified with a windshed.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) In my part of the country, the characteristic winds come in the middle of winter when we most need them, raising temperatures and blowing the snow off the ground and (at least potentially) providing the power to heat homes. We call them “chinooks.” They are part of our lives, in the same way that the “mistral” is part of the life of the Midi, the “bise” of the Lavaux, and the “foehn” of the Schwarzwald. There is even a playful and much noticed little wind that whirls around the church of the Gesu in Rome. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)To treat them as no more than another energy source, “standing reserve”(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)as Heidegger would put it, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)is to disconnect them from the ways in which they have helped determine the character of local plant, animal, and human communities, and in the process to rob them of their individuality and their beauty.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) By the same token, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)they need to be connected in specific, and not simply “functional,” ways to wind turbines if the latter in turn are to share in this beauty.(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)¶(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)I do not want to over-emphasize these (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)communitarian and bioregional perspectives,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) although they (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)should always be important elements in our thinking.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) The point is that (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)//these perspectives allow us to found an aesthetic that is not simply conventional or visual and on which both winds and the machines that capture their energy are beautiful.//(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)//¶ //(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)In my view, these are two sides of the same coin. On one, machines small and simple and inexpensive enough to be locally owned and operated, without the intervention of highly specialized engineers, the creation of dense and extensive turbine arrays, and corporate financing. On the other, machines that have a history, that supply a context, that are sensitive to their sites, and that as a result integrate with at least some landscapes and hence with the communities that have grown up on them. Again to quote Schumacher, whose thinking has in so many ways shaped my own:(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)What is it that we really require from the scientists and technologists?(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) I should answer: (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)We need methods and equipment which are(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)¶ (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)—cheap enough so that they are accessible to everyone; (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)¶ (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)—suitable for small-scale application; (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)¶ (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)—compatible with man’s need for creativity.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)36&#xD;
&#xD;
==== We affirm thing like wind energy.  It solves for a number of reasons.  It is locally contingent which does not efface the history of local communities that establish them.  It allows for more independent community oversight which halts environmental degradation.  It solves for the aff’s concept of beauty.  The aff is entrenched in the Western mindset of making the current model more palatable to the general public.  This, however, only manipulates tastes of contingent communities.  Instead, what is needed is to reopen the structure of wind turbines all together.  This is the critical task of the environmental geographer.  They only create their own resistance. ====&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)Brittain.  2001.  Their author.  Gordon G. Brittain Jr., “Wind, energy, landscape: reconciling nature and technology,” Geography and Philosophy, Vol. 4, 2001 – M.E.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)What(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %), then, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)do I propose? A(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) very (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)different sort of wind turbine.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) A group of us have been working on its development for the past twenty years, although in fact the idea can be traced back to Crete, where thousands of windmills have been spinning for generations on the Lesithi Plain.37(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) In a very schematic way, let me draw your attention to its main features. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)The design parameters are traditional—(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)high solidity, low r.p.m., high torque. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)The rotor consists of sails, furled when the wind blows hard, unfurled when it does not. The machinery is exposed and(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) thoroughly (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)accessible,(%%) clear and comprehensible. (% style=&amp;#34;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)All of it can be repaired by someone(%%) with a rudimentary knowledge of electronics and mechanics, (% style=&amp;#34;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)with the sort of tools used to fix farm machinery. The generators,(%%) gear boxes, and brakes (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)are situated at ground level(%%) and the turbine does not require a crane for either its installation or repair, or any sort of tower.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)38 It is a down-wind machine and tracks easily and freely. In two words, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)it is a “thing” and not a “device.”(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)39 All of Borgmann’s criteria are satisfied.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Sails(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %), of course, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)have a(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) very (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)long history.(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) They were the first way in which humans captured the energy of the wind.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) The context they supply has to do with long voyages and the hopes and fears that attended them, with naval battles fought and races won. Long central in human life, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)they are well-integrated and(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) for this reason,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) among others, (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)//beautiful.//(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)//¶ //(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Sails also allow for engagement and skill.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Anyone who has ever sailed knows what it is like to feel the power of the wind in his hands and to take full advantage of it by shaping the sails in the right sort of way and choosing the best angle of attack. But (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)you do not have to have sailed to use this windmill. All that is necessary is that you have experienced putting up a sheet to dry in the wind or have tried to fold an umbrella.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) How different this experience is from holding up a toy plastic windmill, an experience significant only for young children.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)A sail turbine is sensitive to the wind, turning at lower speeds, moved by it alone and not by gears and motors, furling and unfurling as needs be. Even at top speed, (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)it turns more slowly than conventional wind turbines(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (at less than a third their rate) and is (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)never(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) merely (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)a(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)distracting blur.(%%) Even in large arrays, (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)the(%%) water-pumping (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)sail machines(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) on the Lesithi Plain (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)have a very pleasing appearance.(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)All very well, but (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)what about the efficiency and economy of the sail turbine?(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Whatever intrinsic characteristics it might have, however beautiful it might be, it still has to perform. We have always been able to generate power curves comparable to conventional turbines, with this exception, that we begin to generate electricity at lower wind speeds.40 Our problem up to this point has been the mechanical reliability of the turbine, principally with respect to the furling device. We think we have at long last solved this problem. Otherwise, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)the cost per kilowatt-hour is projected to be somewhere in the vicinity of $0.03, competitive with other, more conventional forms of generation.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶ (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)The comparatively small size and relative simplicity of the sail turbine means that it can be locally owned and operated,(%%) one machine at a time. (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Changes taking place in the American power industry have made this more feasible than ever.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Much of the early resistance to wind energy came from the utilities; in addition to the unreliability of the turbines then available, wind energy did not very well fit the utilities’ “industrial model,” however many efforts were made to conform to that model on the part of the wind energy companies themselves.41 But (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)we have entered a phase in which electrical energy is being de-regulated and de-centralized,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) just the sort of development that Schumacher and others had in mind. It will, I believe, be more and more possible for owners of small numbers of wind turbines, and of the co-operatives into which I see themselves forming, to put their power on the grid, particularly since wind-generated electricity on even the most optimistic projections will never amount to more than ten percent of the total.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) There are, of course, a number of problems with the analogy; but I think that in important respects (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)a number of relatively small machines, working together, will ultimately prove to be more efficient, as well as more beautiful, than a single very large machine,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) in the same way that a number of smaller processors, operating in parallel, surpass the capacity of very large main frame computers.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Finally, and again following Leopold’s lead, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)I want to urge(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)a pluralistic approach.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) If we pay the kind of detailed attention to landscapes to first uncover and then appreciate their beauty, then we must conclude that (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)certain kinds of turbines will “fit” some of these landscapes better than others.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) I have tried to make a case for our own soft foil turbine, the Windjammer. In fact, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)just as not all sails and sailboats are of the same shape and size, varying as a function of the winds and the seas in which they are found and the purposes to which they are put,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) it seems to me that the Windjammer can be adapted in a variety of ways. But there are other turbine designs, some of them not yet imagined, that will “fit” their own landscapes better. To this point, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)governments and utilities,(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) and the engineers they fund, have (% style=&amp;#34;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)presuppose(%%)d almost from the outset the viability of (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)a particular design, and devoted almost all of their resources to “improving” it.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) In the process, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)they have discounted plans and ideas that might be more acceptable aesthetically. One(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) central (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)result is that they have also created large-scale and determined resistance to wind energy.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)Along the same lines, (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)//too much effort has been devoted to making the conventional large, bladed turbine palatable to the general public. This effort has been predicated on the essential subjectivity of aesthetic considerations and the thought that taste can be manipulated.//(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) I have argued that (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)the aesthetic ideals taken as normative in our own cultural tradition have at the very least an important objective component.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) It follows from the nature of these ideals, however they are further to be construed, that (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)only “things,” in their depth and complexity, can be beautiful. Rather than relapse into subjectivity or manipulate taste, we need to re-open the basic design and aesthetic questions,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) questions (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)which(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %), I have tried to suggest, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)cannot very well be separated from the character of contemporary technology or the ways in which we take up with the world.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Perhaps (% style=&amp;#34;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)//raising these sorts of questions about human and natural landscapes is a main task of philosophers interested in geography.//</headline></objectSummary><objectSummary><link rel="http://www.xwiki.org/rel/object" href="http://opencaselist.paperlessdebate.com/xwiki/rest/wikis/opencaselist/spaces/Texas-San%20Antonio/pages/nerison-stroud%20Neg/objects/Admin.EntryClass/11"/><link rel="http://www.xwiki.org/rel/properties" href="http://opencaselist.paperlessdebate.com/xwiki/rest/wikis/opencaselist/spaces/Texas-San%20Antonio/pages/nerison-stroud%20Neg/objects/Admin.EntryClass/11/properties"/><id>opencaselist:Texas-San Antonio.nerison-stroud Neg:478521fd-f88c-44bc-9979-3c75a948764b</id><guid>478521fd-f88c-44bc-9979-3c75a948764b</guid><pageId>opencaselist:Texas-San Antonio.nerison-stroud Neg</pageId><wiki>opencaselist</wiki><space>Texas-San Antonio</space><pageName>nerison-stroud Neg</pageName><className>Admin.EntryClass</className><number>11</number><headline>==== They want unrestricted art. Proliferation of difference. Instead do art like Andy Warhol. ====&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt;mso-fareast-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family:Times-Roman;mso-fareast-language:AR-SA&amp;#34; %) &#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt;mso-fareast-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-font-family:Times-Roman;mso-fareast-language:AR-SA&amp;#34; %) &#xD;
&#xD;
==== Waking life dream of a pimped, prostituted encounter; I recall the virtuous virgin //“alterity”// - before even able to speak her beautiful name - pure and passionate beyond comprehension and touch she still calls out to me in the melodramatic tones of a mute muse – a radical siren echoing from afar like a ray of light just now reaching, and then already past, reflecting from the screen of my retina - that star burned out several years ago just now seen in all its transparency – //“what else could I do – I said I will see what I can do” –// ====&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
 &#xD;
&#xD;
==== //“First as authentic event and then being repeated as farce.”(% class=&amp;#34;FootnoteCharacters FootnoteCharacters&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Calibri; mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;ＭＳ ゴシック~&amp;#34;;mso-fareast-theme-font:major-fareast; mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-theme-font:major-bidi; mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA&amp;#34; %)**1**url:#_ftn1||name=&amp;#34;_ftnref1&amp;#34;//(%%)  Where the Other once appeared the same now lies, faint and flaccid, infinitely repeating.  //Difference// - proliferating from all directions, every angle, coaxed from each corner, crawl space and corridor to concealment, now from, into the light… and hence Otherness nowhere to be found.  It seems: ====&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;tag&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
 &#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;WW-Default&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;cite&amp;#34; %)Nowicki 2008(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %)(Joanna Nowicki, Maître de Conférence and Dean of the Hannah Arendt Institute at Université Paris-Est Marne la Vallée, France - The Man of Confluences : a Model of Education for the XXIst Century Gentleman ? -  “L&amp;#39;homme des confins, pour une anthropologie interculturelle&amp;#34;, CNRS Edtions 2008.  Translated by Michaël Oustinoff)&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;tag&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
 &#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:13.5pt;text-align:justify;text-justify: inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; %)The (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)exploration of the New World has been complete(%%)d(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:14.0pt&amp;#34; %) to the point that some even think that travel has become impossible (and they sadly conclude that (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)the only option left is tourism(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:14.0pt&amp;#34; %)) (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)and so has the encounter with radical alterity, for the Other has been reduced to an alter ego.(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; %) Immigration, too, has changed its face, because the countries that used to supply unskilled labour are today in a position to export their highly-skilled workers, whose grey matter is sold on the same conditions as the West’s(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:14.0pt&amp;#34; %), something (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; %)which considerably modifies the relationships between the people involved(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:14.0pt&amp;#34; %). (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %)More often than not, this corresponds to what is called expatriation, that is, living in a country different from the one where we were born but not in order(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:14.0pt&amp;#34; %) to leave an emigrating country for traditional economic reasons. (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; %)It cannot be equated to exile (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)either(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:14.0pt&amp;#34; %), because the people under consideration may return to their native countries because they(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt;&amp;#34; %)were (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; %)not sentenced to banishment(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt;&amp;#34; %), another factor which changes their perception of those whom circumstances have brought them to live with.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:13.5pt;text-align:justify;text-justify: inter-ideograph;text-indent:27.0pt;mso-pagination:none;text-autospace:ideograph-numeric&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt;&amp;#34; %)If we bear in mind all these geopolitical, sociological and human upheavals, the time has probably come when it is legitimate to envisage another kind of intercultural anthropology which would be built on a new interdisciplinary approach, borrowing from the human and social sciences their most valid tools to enable us to assess the importance of the image, of discourse and representation, be it cultural or political, whose downside is the emergence of stereotypes which can never be done away with and which sometimes are dangerous insofar as they oversimplify issues and are easily instrumentalized by the ideologues of violent conflicts.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:13.5pt;text-align:justify;text-justify: inter-ideograph;text-indent:27.0pt;mso-pagination:none;text-autospace:ideograph-numeric&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt;&amp;#34; %)When you find yourself in Europe, there is no urgent need to look for examples of interculturality in remote, exotic lands. In point of fact, the issue of (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)cultural cohabitation(%%), which lies(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)at the(%%) very (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)heart of democratic debate today must be totally reassessed in(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)the(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)light of(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt;&amp;#34; %) the recent reuniting of the European continent and the disappearance of the two-bloc confrontation which was, as it were, (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; %)the (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)dominant political analysis (%%)grid (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)obliterating all the rest and obscuring the far greater complexity of(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)the (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)real relationships(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)between cultures. (% class=&amp;#34;FootnoteCharacters FootnoteCharacters&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 12pt; font-size: 8pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 12pt; font-family: Calibri; mso-fareast-font-family: ~&amp;#34;ＭＳ 明朝~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-ansi-language: EN-US; mso-fareast-language: EN-US; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA&amp;#34; %)2url:#_ftn2||name=&amp;#34;_ftnref2&amp;#34;&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
 &#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;line-height:10.0pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:10.0pt; font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)Jean Baudrillard. “Between Difference and Singularity: An Open Discussion with Jean Baudrillard.” June 2002. EGS. http:~/~/www.egs.edu/faculty/jean-baudrillard/articles/between-difference-and-singularity/.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;line-height:10.0pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)**Baudrillard:**(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt&amp;#34; %) No,(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)__we are in a culture of difference__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %), of culture as difference, a multicultural organization. Culture as singularity is more than difference.(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)__Difference can be easily organized into a system which generates structure and meaning. Culture__(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %)as such(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)__has no finality, no meaning__(%%)__, it&amp;#39;s a symbolic act and in this sense (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)it&amp;#39;s beyond differences which are only oppositional structures(%%)__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %). Singularity is a symbolic acting, a collective acting.(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)__Primitive__(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %)societies and(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background: lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)__cultures are__(%%)__ not different, they&amp;#39;re very (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)singular(%%)__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %), it&amp;#39;s not the same.(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background: lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)__Today, all cultures__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %)of the world(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)__are in multicultural ensembles as differences, together as the megaculture of difference__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %), which is very opposed to the original singularity of culture(%%).&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;line-height:10.0pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)**Schirmacher:**(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt&amp;#34; %) They are more like different brands.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;line-height:10.0pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)**Baudrillard:**(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)__They can be juxtaposed and collected altogether in a museum__(%%).&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;line-height: 10.0pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)**Audience:** Do you think it&amp;#39;s time that artists use their strengths for something else than making objects? Is there something an artist can do better than just contributing to the art market?&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)**Baudrillard:** An extension of art action today, in a very general sense, is performance. Maybe(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__art is everywhere at this point, and__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri&amp;#34; %)__ as such __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__it&amp;#39;s possible to make art of everything__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %). I&amp;#39;m afraid(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) __that&amp;#39;s a pure extension of the readymade__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %). As a game traditional art has a rule, it has to invent a scene other than reality. It must not work so much in the real world, to transform it in political, social, therapeutic ways, that&amp;#39;s not art, art has a stronger, more radical definition for me.(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) __Today__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %), it&amp;#39;s a fact,(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__art is an interacting, multi-directional activity, but that&amp;#39;s a very degenerated art__.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)**Schirmacher:** What do you mean by radical?&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)**Baudrillard:**(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__Radical__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)would be the separation apart from any meaning, any finality, any causality.(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__Art would be a thing itself__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; font-family:Calibri;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %),(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) nothing but(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__a singularity, __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)__and as such it cannot be anything in the real world__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %). The art world would be anything else,(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) __it should be incompatible with reality__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %). Traditional art was integrated in the symbolic order of the culture, but it was a radical illusion. In old times there wasn&amp;#39;t reality. Now this illusion is lost, and art has lost its privileged position inside this symbolic order.(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) __Now we have to do with reality, and__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)unfortunately(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__contemporary art has fallen into the trap of reality, it becomes real, and soon it will be hyperreal__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)in accordance with our surroundings. I would say rather than evolution(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) __it is an involution__.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)**Ulfers:** I agree with your notion with the singularity of culture, I&amp;#39;m wondering though if you are, I don&amp;#39;t think you are, talking about a closed system here, because in order to have singularity you need to have, just for the sake of comparison, a relation to otherness. That otherness is not to be confused with globalism or globalization, but we need some way to be capable of differentiating yourself from another in order to be single.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)**Baudrillard:** I agree that(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__the singularity has__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)paradoxically(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__to do with alterity__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %). It&amp;#39;s a paradigm(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__which is__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)__ highly __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__opposed to &amp;#34;identity/difference__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)__&amp;#34;__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %), which is our paradigm, I would say. Singularity and alterity is a double game, I agree(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %).&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)**Ulfers:** But that&amp;#39;s not to be confused with what you have defined as globalization, or multiculturalism.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)**Baudrillard:** Yes because(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__we can oppose this paradigm of the totality of globalization, where all differences can be integrated, but as differences, not as singularities__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %). One of(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__the strategies of this new order of the world is to transform singularities into differences. As differences they are able to be integrated__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)into the global(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %).(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) __As singularities they cannot__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)__. It&amp;#39;s an immense attempt of this global world to reduce and annihilate all singularities in order to be integrated into an undifferentiated world__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %). This world of differences, this culture of differences is an alibi for a culture of indifferentiation(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %).&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)**Audience:** Regarding the stockpiling of culture, where is the room for the artist to have resistance? Do we go underground, like the rat? True culture, like evil, cannot truly be suppressed(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %).&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)**Baudrillard:** Of course, you may, or can, or must, but you must create your underground, because now(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__there&amp;#39;s no more underground, no more avant-garde, no more marginality. You can create your personal underground, your own black hole, your own singularity. The bad fate is that everyone can do that, but it will never create a collective symbolic order__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %), it will be an exceptional, special creation, and today we can see that.(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) __Creative initiative__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)maybe(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) __as a subjective act is very original but it doesn&amp;#39;t create a symbolic movement__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %). That&amp;#39;s the problem(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %).(% class=&amp;#34;MsoFootnoteReference MsoFootnoteReference&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; font-size: 12pt&amp;#34; %)3url:#_ftn3||name=&amp;#34;_ftnref3&amp;#34;&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
 &#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
 &#xD;
&#xD;
==== Yet, we continue to strive for this utopia achieved and an orgy concluded - more contact, clearer channels, total information and perfect communication.  Life long access to learning, better forms of knowledge and means of obtaining it - increased understanding and exposure to all worldly things, entities, and concepts – tolerance, acceptance, and the right to be different no matter how strange you seem.  //“We are procurers of encounter, pimps of interfacing and interactivity”//, A world absent suffering, and more importantly one that gives us the all ability to live another day, hopefully till the end of time which has been postponed indefinitely  – a world of rational animals, of political beings collectively working to bring about a brighter tomorrow by envisioning it today.  Don’t worry, even those who can’t read are encouraged to, and win debates today.  Nothing is greater than this, I fucking promise!  Now give me that Christian side-hug! ====&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) &#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:10.0pt&amp;#34; %)Jean Baudrillard. “The Conspiracy of Art.” The Conspiracy of Art. 2005. Page 25-27.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;mso-line-height-alt: 10.0pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)__The illusion of desire has been lost in__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)the ambient(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) __pornography__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) and contemporary art has lost the desire of illusion. In porn, nothing is left to desire.(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__After__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri&amp;#34; %)__ the __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__orgies and the liberation of all desires, we have__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri&amp;#34; %)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__moved into__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)the transsexual,(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__the transparency of sex__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)__, with signs and images __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__erasing all its secrets __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)__and ambiguity__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %). Transsexual, in the sense that it now has nothing to do with the illusion of desire, only with the hyperreality of the image(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %).&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;mso-line-height-alt: 10.0pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)            (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__The same is true for art, which has__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)also(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__lost the desire for illusion, and__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)instead(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__raises__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__everything to aesthetic banality__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family: Calibri&amp;#34; %), becoming transaesthetic.(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__For art, the orgy of modernity consisted in the__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)heady(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__deconstruction of __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri&amp;#34; %)__the object and of __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__representation.__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri&amp;#34; %)__ During that period, the aesthetic illusion remained very powerful__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %), just as the illusion of desire was for sex. The energy of(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) __sexual difference__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %), which moved through all the figures of desire,(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) __corresponded, in art, to the energy of dissociation from reality (cubism, abstraction, expressionism)__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family: Calibri&amp;#34; %). Both, however, corresponded to the will to crack the secret of desire and the secret of the object.(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__Up until the disappearance of__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)these two powerful configurations-the scene of desire, the scene of(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__illusion-in favor of the same__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)transsexual,(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) __transaesthetic obscenity, __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__the obscenity of visibility__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)__, the relentless transparency of all things. In reality, __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__there is no longer any pornography, since it is virtually everywhere__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family: Calibri&amp;#34; %) The essence of pornography permeates all visual and televisual techniques(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %).&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;mso-line-height-alt: 10.0pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)            (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)Maybe we are just acting out the comedy of art, just as other societies acted out the comedy of ideology, just as Italian society (though it is not alone) keeps acting out the comedy of power, just as we keep acting out the comedy of porn in the obscene advertising pictures of women&amp;#39;s bodies.(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__Perpetual striptease, fantasies of exposed organs, sexual blackmail__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %): if all this were true, it would indeed be unbearable. Fortunately, it is all is too obvious to be true. The transparency is too good to be true. As for(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__art__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %), it(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__is too superficial to be truly null__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)and void.(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__There must be some underlying mystery__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) Like for anamorphosis: there must be an angle from which all of this useless excess of sex and signs becomes meaningful, but, for the time being, we can only experience it with ironic indifference. In this unreality of porn, in this insignificance of art, is there a negative enigma, a mysterious thread, or, who knows, an ironic form of our destiny? If everything becomes too obvious to be true, maybe there still is a chance for illusion. What lies hidden behind this falsely transparent world? Another kind of intelligence or a terminal lobotomy? (Modern) art managed to be a part of the accursed share, a kind of dramatic alternative to reality, by translating the rush of unreality in reality.(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) __But what could art possibly mean in a world that has already become hyperrealist, cool, transparent, marketable?__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)What can porn mean in a world made pornographic beforehand?(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__All it can do is make a final, paradoxical wink-the wink of reality laughing at itself in its most hyperrealist form__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %), of sex laughing at itself in its most exhibitionist form,(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__of art laughing at itself and at its own disappearance in its most artificial form, irony__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %). In any case, the dictatorship of images is an ironic dictatorship. Yet this irony itself is no longer part of the accursed share. It now belongs to insider trading, the shameful and hidden complicity binding the artist who uses his or her aura of derision against the bewildered and doubtful masses. Irony is also part of the conspiracy of art(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %).&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;mso-line-height-alt: 10.0pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)            (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)As long as art was making use of its own disappearance and the disappearance of its object, it still was a major enterprise.(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) __But __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__art trying to recycle itself indefinitely__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)__ by storming reality?__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)The majority of(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) __contemporary art has attempted__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)to do(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) __precisely that __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__by confiscating banality, waste and mediocrity__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)__ as values and ideologies. These countless installations and performances __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__are__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)__ merely __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__compromising with the state of things__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %), and with all the past forms of art history. Raising originality, banality and nullity to the level of values or even to perverse aesthetic pleasure. Of course,(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__all of this mediocrity claims to transcend itself__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)__ by moving art to a second, ironic level. __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__But it is just as empty__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)and insignificant on the second as the first level.(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__The passage to the aesthetic level salvages nothing; on the contrary, it is mediocrity squared. It claims to be null- &amp;#34;I am null! I am null!&amp;#34; -and it truly is null__.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;mso-line-height-alt: 10.0pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)            (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__Therein lies all the duplicity of contemporary art__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family: Calibri&amp;#34; %): asserting nullity, insignificance, meaninglessness,(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__striving for nullity when already null__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)and void. Striving for emptiness when already empty.(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__Claiming superficiality in superficial terms__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %). Nullity, however, is a secret quality that cannot be claimed by just anyone. Insignificance-real insignificance, the victorious challenge to meaning, the shedding of sense, the art of the disappearance of meaning-is the rare quality of a few exceptional works that never strive for it. There is an initiatory form of Nothingness, or an initiatory form of Evil. And then there are the inside traders, the counterfeiters of nullity, the snobs of nullity, of all those who prostitute Nothingness to value, who prostitute Evil for useful ends. The counterfeiters must not be allowed free reign. When Nothing surfaces in signs, when Nothingness emerges at the very heart of the sign system, that is the fundamental event of art. The poetic operation is to make Nothingness rise from the power of signs-not banality or indifference toward reality but radical illusion. Warhol is thus truly null, in the sense that he reintroduces nothingness into the heart of the image. He turns nullity and insignificance into an event that he changes into a fatal strategy of the image(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %).&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;line-height: 10.0pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:7.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)                  (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)Other artists only have a commercial strategy of nullity, one to which they give a marketable form, the sentimental form of commodity, as Baudelaire said. (% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)__They hide behind their own nullity and behind the metastases of the discourse on art, which generously promotes this nullity as a value__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (within the art market as well, obviously). In a way,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 7.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)__it is worse than nothing, because it means nothing and it nonetheless exists, providing itself with all the right reasons to exist. This paranoia in collusion with art means that there is no longer any possible critical judgment__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 7.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %),(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family: Calibri&amp;#34; %) and(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:7.0pt; font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri;background: lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)__only an amiable, necessarily genial sharing of nullity. Therein lies the conspiracy of art__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:7.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)and its primal scene,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:7.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)__transmitted by all of the openings, hangings, exhibitions, restorations, collections, donations and speculations__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 7.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %),(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family: Calibri&amp;#34; %) and that cannot be undone in any known universe, since it has hidden itself from thought behind the mystification of images(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:7.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %).(% class=&amp;#34;MsoFootnoteReference MsoFootnoteReference&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 7pt; font-family: Calibri; font-size: 8pt&amp;#34; %)**4**url:#_ftn4||name=&amp;#34;_ftnref4&amp;#34;&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
 &#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;tag&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt&amp;#34; %) &#xD;
&#xD;
==== Utopia achieved, complete with empowering “a” – all distance transcended, borders and corresponding lands of separation eliminated, the barriers brought down, lines erased, and walls collapsed, reduced to rubble simultaneously smoothed out, leveled in a unified instant. ====&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
 &#xD;
&#xD;
==== One must finally ask… ====&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
 &#xD;
&#xD;
==== What are you doing after the orgy? ====&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
 &#xD;
&#xD;
==== US individuals, us citizens, patriots, and politicians (or possibly //politisans// if you’re cool enough), us rational actors, and most aptly and universally //us// debaters - labor for such world, pursue, if not demand it to be.  Inclusion for all, maximize diversity, all voices heard and terms of such exchange agreed upon in advance – (i)nsured fairness for all, a level playing field, equal opportunity to be, become, even fantasize about that person to be given your name. Let’s do it again //‘The imagination in power!’ ‘Take your desires for reality’//  - No more barricades or barriers, even the attitudinally inherent appear tabled - Grant more visas, remove the caps, expand eligibility, benefits, admissibility – communication guarantees, and the right to productive deliberation. Come one, come all – Welcome to the greatest show on earth!  Inclusion for all at half the price of admission.  ====&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
 &#xD;
&#xD;
==== Close your eyes, give me your hand… ====&#xD;
&#xD;
==== Do you feel my heart beating, do you understand… ====&#xD;
&#xD;
==== Do you feel the same? ====&#xD;
&#xD;
==== Or am I only dreaming? ====&#xD;
&#xD;
==== Or is this..(% class=&amp;#34;FootnoteCharacters FootnoteCharacters&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; mso-ascii-font-family: Calibri; mso-hansi-font-family: Calibri; font-weight: normal; mso-bidi-font-weight: bold; font-size: 8pt; font-family: Calibri; mso-fareast-font-family: ~&amp;#34;ＭＳ ゴシック~&amp;#34;; mso-fareast-theme-font: major-fareast; mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-theme-font: major-bidi; mso-ansi-language: EN-US; mso-fareast-language: EN-US; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA&amp;#34; %)//**5**//url:#_ftn5||name=&amp;#34;_ftnref5&amp;#34;(%%) ====&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
 &#xD;
&#xD;
==== A duel form: Carnival and Cannibal, Difference qua Otherness!  It seems we have mistaken the gape for the abyss: “These days everything is described in terms of difference, but otherness is not the same thing as difference. One might even say that difference is what destroys otherness” winking its beautiful brown eye if to quietly seduce us in believing it stares back.  Carnivalization - the hegemony, universality, and incorporation of all into of the good, the psychodrama of difference – an incestuous inception -“falling barriers and great reductions in real distance must of themselves compensate somewhere by means of new partitions and unanticipated gaps.”  The birth of Corky Lecter: “the corpse-like, viral Other: the compound form of all the varieties of otherness done to death by our system”, “… an immigrant by force of circumstance or a voluntary immigrant but at some point, the question of the Other is no longer relevant because a kind of fusion occurs.”(% class=&amp;#34;MsoFootnoteReference MsoFootnoteReference&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Calibri; mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;ＭＳ ゴシック~&amp;#34;;mso-fareast-theme-font:major-fareast; mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;;mso-bidi-theme-font:major-bidi; mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA&amp;#34; %)//**6**//url:#_ftn6||name=&amp;#34;_ftnref6&amp;#34;(%%) ====&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
// //&#xD;
&#xD;
==== “All good things to those who wait”(% class=&amp;#34;FootnoteCharacters FootnoteCharacters&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; mso-ascii-font-family: Calibri; mso-hansi-font-family: Calibri; font-weight: normal; mso-bidi-font-weight: bold; font-size: 8pt; font-family: Calibri; mso-fareast-font-family: ~&amp;#34;ＭＳ ゴシック~&amp;#34;; mso-fareast-theme-font: major-fareast; mso-bidi-font-family: ~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-theme-font: major-bidi; mso-ansi-language: EN-US; mso-fareast-language: EN-US; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA&amp;#34; %)//**7**//url:#_ftn7||name=&amp;#34;_ftnref7&amp;#34;(%%) ====&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;mso-line-height-alt: 10.0pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) &#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;line-height: 10.0pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)Jean Baudrillard. “Art Between Utopia and Anticipation.” The Conspiracy of Art. 2005. Page 95(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %).&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;mso-line-height-alt: 10.0pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) &#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)__Ever since the 19th century, art has wanted to be useless. It turned this uselessness into a reason for praise (which was not true of classical art where__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family: Calibri&amp;#34; %), in a world that was not yet real or objective,(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) __usefulness was not even considered)__.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)            __By extension of this principle, __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__making any object useless would be enough to make it a work of art. This is__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)__ precisely __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__what the readymade does when it merely divests an object of its function,__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)__ without changing anything about it, to turn it into a museum piece. __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__It__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)__ is sufficient to __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__make reality__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)__ itself __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__a useless function to turn it into an art object,__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)__ prey to the all-consuming aesthetic of banality__.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)            (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)By the same token, older things, coming from the past and therefore useless, automatically acquire an aesthetic aura. Their displacement in time is the equivalent of Duchamp&amp;#39;s gesture; they become readymades as well, nostalgic vestiges resuscitated in our museum universe(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %).&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)            (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)One could extrapolate this aesthetic transformation to(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) __material production__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)as a whole.(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__As soon as__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)it reaches a level where(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__it can no longer be exchanged in terms of__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)social(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__wealth, it becomes a__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)giant(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__surrealist object, seized by an all-consuming aesthetic__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)and is included everywhere in a sort of virtual museum. Like for the readymade,(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__an in-situ museification in the form of dormant industry for every technical waste land__.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)            __The logic of uselessness could only lead contemporary art to a predilection for waste-that which is useless by definition. Through refuse, the figuration of refuse, the obsession with refuse, art strives to display its own uselessness. It presents its non-use value, its non-exchange value-while still being sold at very high prices__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %).&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) &#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;tag&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
 &#xD;
&#xD;
==== //Tugg Speedman: //(% style=&amp;#34;mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri;mso-hansi-font-family: Calibri;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)There were times while I was playing Jack where I felt...(%%) ====&#xD;
&#xD;
==== //Tugg Speedman: (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)...retarded. Like, really retarded.//(%%) ====&#xD;
&#xD;
==== Kirk Lazarus: (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Damn!(%%) ====&#xD;
&#xD;
==== //Tugg Speedman: (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)In a weird way I had to sort of just free myself up to believe that is was ok to be stupid or dumb.//(%%) ====&#xD;
&#xD;
==== Kirk Lazarus: (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)To be a moron.(%%) ====&#xD;
&#xD;
