==== Kirk Lazarus: (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Like the dumbest mother fucker that ever lived.(%%) ====&#xD;
&#xD;
==== //Tugg Speedman: pause (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)When I was playing the character.//(%%) ====&#xD;
&#xD;
==== Kirk Lazarus: (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Everybody knows you never do a full retard.(%%) ====&#xD;
&#xD;
==== //Tugg Speedman: (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)What do you mean?//(%%) ====&#xD;
&#xD;
==== Kirk Lazarus: (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Check it out. Dustin Hoffman, &amp;#39;Rain Man,&amp;#39; look retarded, act retarded, not retarded. Count toothpicks to your cards. Autistic, sure. Not retarded. You know Tom Hanks, &amp;#39;Forrest Gump.&amp;#39; Slow, yes. Retarded, maybe. Braces on his legs. But he charmed the pants off Nixon and won a ping-pong competition. That ain&amp;#39;t retarded. Then there was Sean Penn in ‘I Am Sam.’ He went full retard. Left the Oscars empty-handed. You went full retard, man. Never go full retard.(%%) ====&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;tag&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt&amp;#34; %) &#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;tag&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; %)BAUDRILLARD 2010 (Jean, Carnival and Cannibal: Ventriloqous Evil.  Translated by Chris Turner.  Seagull Books 2010, pages 55-69)&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) &#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;card&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt; font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)This is the state of things in which (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri;background:lime;mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)the system has snaffled all the mechanisms of simulation, parody, irony and self-derision;(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri&amp;#34; %) it has snaffled the whole of the negative and, with it, critical thought, (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)leaving(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri&amp;#34; %) the latter (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)only the //ghost// of the truth.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;card&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt; font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)All the same, things are perhaps not settled once and for all, since the rules have changed (or perhaps there are no rules nay longer) and the new situation is as follows: (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)by denying(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) the very existence of (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)Evil(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (all the forms of radical, heterogeneous, (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)irreconcilable otherness(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)), (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)by making the negative a kind of prehistoric vestige,(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)Good has,(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) in a way (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)given Evil its freedom(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)  (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)In seeking to be Absolute Good, it has freed Evil from all dependency and given it back its autonomous power, which is no longer simply the power of the negative but the power to change the rules of the game(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %).  Something resurfaces here of the Manichaean heresy, which asserted the originality and singularity of Evil.  And one can feel something analogous playing itself out in the depths of this integral reality.  (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)As the old forms of revolt that defied the dominant power find themselves swallowed up by the system itself, a new counter-finality is springing up(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) from all the interstices of the system, (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)a challenge to the supremacy of Good, (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)infiltrating and breaking up that reality much more radically than the work of the negative did.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;card&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)When the power of the negative fades(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %), when the prohibitions, controls, inequalities and differences disappear one by one, the better to internalize themselves in the mental sphere(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %), it is at this point that Evil, as undesirable alien, becomes Ventriloqous.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;card&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt; font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)The Banque Nationale de Paris had a famous advertising slogan in the 1970s: ‘Your money interests me!’, which sums up better than any critical analysis can do, the ignominy of capital.  Denunciations of what ignominy were as old as the hills, but what was new and scandalous was having these words come direct from the bankers themselves, the truth coming straight from the mouth of Evil, so to speak.  The truth came straight from the mouth of the dominant power itself, and that power, secure in the knowledge of its total immunity, admitted its ‘crime’ quite openly.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;card&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt; font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)The most recent profession of faith of this same kind was uttered by Patrick Le Lay, the CEO of the French TV channel TF1.  ‘Let’s be realistic’, he said, ‘TF1’s job is to help Coca-Cola shift product… For an advertising message to get through, the viewers brain has to be receptive to it.  It’s the aim of our programs to make that brain receptive, that is to say, to entertain it and relax it, to prepare it between two messages.  What we sell to Coca-Cola is receptive human brain time… Nothing is more difficult than obtaining that receptiveness’.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;card&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt; font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)We have to pay tribute to this amazing declaration of principle for its outstanding professional cynicism (which it shares with many other similar declarations, such as that of the French post office: ‘Money has no sex, but that shouldn’t prevent it from reproducing’).&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;card&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt; font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)But this is not the point.  What struck people in the Le Lay case was the barefaced cheek of the statement, which fascinated even those who condemned it.  Isn’t this immoral offhandedness the mask of a greater freedom of expression than is shown in the eternal stereotyped language of critical protest?&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;card&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt; font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)And this is, in fact, the problem – that (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri;background:lime;mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)the truth has been stolen by an ‘arrogant’ discourse that thwarts any form of criticism by short circuiting it.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)  The real scandal doesn’t lie so much in technocratic cynicism as in the breaking of a rule of our social and political game, which says that the corruption is on one side and the protest against on the other.  If the corrupt no longer respect this protocol, if they lay out their hands for all to see, without even doing us the courtesy of hypocrisy, then the ritual mechanism of critical condemnation is taken from us.  This is capital laid bare by the capitalist themselves.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;card&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt; font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)Le Lay is stealing from us the only power we have left; he is stealing condemnation!  This is where the scandal lies.  Otherwise, how are we to explain all these outraged reactions to someone spilling the beans on an open secret?&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;card&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)Instead of condemning Evil from the standpoint of Good(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) – the eternal moral position – (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri;background:lime;mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)he is speaking Evil from the standpoint of Evil.(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)  (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)And immediately, all that excels in arrogance (Le Pen, cynicism (Le Lay), pornography (the Abu Ghraib pictures) and myth-o-mania (the fabulous story of Marie L.) is, by that very token, (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri;background:lime;mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)more effective at unmasking the truth of the system than traditional critique!&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;card&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt; font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)If the truth hits the mark and hits home with people, this is because it comes, paradoxically, from the horizon of Evil.  We always expect it to come from the side of Enlightenment and Reason – which was perhaps the case historically – but today it is from the horizon of Evil that the truth emerges as an unexpected event, deriving all its force from coming from the place one least expects it.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;card&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)All the discourses of Good are ravaged by ambivalence(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %).  (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)This is particularly visible in the relationship to stupidity, which is the murkiest, but also the most direct and massive expression of this ventriloquousness of Evil.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)  Philippe Muray has magnificently described this beatification, this grotesque pacification of the real world, this festive reduction in perpetuity of the whole of modernity to a party.  Now, it is precisely here, (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri;background:lime;mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)in this extension of the domain of Farce, that Ventriloquous Evil advances on all sides, establishing the hegemony of stupidity – which is the equivalent of hegemony(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) plain and simple.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;card&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt; font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)Of all the modalities in which the proscribed negative can show through in ventriloquos mode, (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)stupidity is both the most banal and the most mysterious.  Better, it becomes a source of energy – and a source of hidden truth(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) – since, no longer expecting anything from a higher instance, we are reduced to this subterranean one, (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)whose energy is inexhaustible(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %), since it comes to us from the immensity of stupidity itself(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %).  We must then – and Muray clearly saw this – draw from it all its innate energy, allow it to deploy itself in all its self-conceit; (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)we must allow Evil to speak ‘through the belly’.  We have to let this masquerade, this banality of Evil work at its own derision.  This is the ‘intelligence of Evil’(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)  Moreover, (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)in the absence now of an active power of the negative, where could we get energy from today if not from a violent abreaction to this ambient stupidity?&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;card&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)As soon as Good rules and claims to embody the truth, it is Evil that comes through.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;card&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)Let us take the No to the European referendum.  It was clearly stupidity that voted No; it was statistically the most stupid (the backward, the retarded) who voted No, but that stupidity was precisely the intelligence of Evil.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;card&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)It was Ventriloqous Evil that replied ‘No’(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Calibri; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)to the referendum.  (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)Not the spirit of the Negative which, like the ‘Yes’, lends its assent to Political Reason.  (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)But an illogical No, resistant to political Reason, and shot through with the exigency not to be annexed or taken hostage by any model whatever(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) – even an ideal one ((% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)especially not an ideal one!(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)) – (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)the exigency not to lend itself to the dialectical stratagem: ‘Your No is a No to Europe as it is, but a Yes to Europe as it should be!’&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;card&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt; font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)There is no difference between the ‘free market’ Yes and the European ‘social’ No.  (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri;background:lime;mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)This(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt; font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) is why the (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)No(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %), which (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)is merely a No to a particular kind of Europe, isn’t really a No – the only No that (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)genuinely constitutes an event is this strange, non-political, non-dialectical, elusive No, since it runs counter to enlightened self-interest.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Calibri;background:lime;mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)  (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)It is a No that isn’t the opposite of a Yes(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (the No of the things that can exist without their opposites), but might be said to be closer to (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)a silent rejection(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) of the kind that makes Bartelby say, ‘I would prefer not to!  (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)I am not playing the game! (But without aspiring to provide a reason(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Calibri; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %))’&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;card&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)You have to be able to fight everything that wishes to do Good to you.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;card&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:0in&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) &#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
 &#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; %)Jed Rasula. “Brutalities of the Vanguard.” Contemporary Literature, 35:4. Winter 1994.&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
 &#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %)The avant-garde exposes, at its own expense, the remorseless appetite of the bourgeoisie (or late capitalism, culture industry, and so on), its rapacious cannibalizing of otherness and remorseless endocolonization of itself. The appetite of capital is in turn replicated by the industry of commentary and metacommentary, in which there is no longer much difference between the frenzy of the press corps and the crowds at an MLA convention. So Mann arrives at the lugubrious spectacle of a “masocriticism endlessly postulating its own torment,” “an interminable discourse of termination.” His is itself an exemplary demonstration of masocriticism: is not the holographic style an inventive way of masochistically revisiting the same trauma center again and again? What does Mann intend by participating in, and perpetuating, a discursive momentum that he clearly sees expended in futility (or worse, in complicity with what it would oppose)? His sentiments are guided by(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background: lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)__Baudrillard__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %), who(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)__reads a__(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %)certain(%%) __sullen (% style=&amp;#34;background: lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)resistance on the part of the masses&amp;#39; refusal to vote(%%)__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %), for instance,(%%) __not (% style=&amp;#34;background: lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)as(%%) indifference but (% style=&amp;#34;background: lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)a silent scorn at the stakes of the game(%%)__.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %) Mann would appear to recite a normative protocol in the conviction that the system will finally be overcome by the giddiness with which it processes and recuperates every possible position and voice. “It might be that the last task of theory is to exhaust theory itself, to push its terms until they disintegrate or, as Baudrillard would say, &amp;#39;implode&amp;#39;: &amp;#39;my way it to make ideas appear, but as soon as they appear I try to make them disappear&amp;#39;.” Eventually (such is the hope) we stop paying attention to the fates of individual ideas and begin to see the larger picture, which is a cycle of appearance/disappearance, opposition/recuperation, perturbation/resolution – the cycle that reconfirms the priority of its own holomovement ( the expectoration of global capital) with every display of a normalized exception. The tradition of(%%) __informed (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)critique(%%)__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %), Mann wants to say,(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)__has__(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %)long since(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)__become a tradition__(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %)that is(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)__most effective in demonstrating its own cancellation__(%%)__, or its own eventual accommodation to the hegemonic norms of a dominant culture. Even (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)the(%%) most exhilarating (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)acts(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)of critical repudiation(%%)__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %)– and this is why(%%) __the avant-garde__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %)is an exemplary case –(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)__are__(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %)primarily(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime; mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)__excitations local to the grotesque and shameless body of capital__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %), or(%%) __they are the moments (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)that //circulate//, since circulation as such //is// the holomovement of global capital.(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)As(%%)__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %)the current spectacle of(%%) __Howard Stern and (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)Rush Limbaugh demonstrates(%%)__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %)(and they are the demonstration of prior demonstrations),(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)__it makes no difference whether sales are motivated by__(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %)love or hate(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %),(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) __adulation or revulsion: if it sells, it sells__(%%).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %) And discourse cannot resist the tautology. “One must therefore proceed in the certainty that …(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)__criticism no longer speaks the voice of alterity__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt&amp;#34; %), or speaks it only in order to cancel what is always left of it … and that(%%) __if (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)difference must be discovered it is precisely a difference from us(%%)__(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %).”&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoBodyText&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)            (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)The logical conclusion of Mann&amp;#39;s views on the contamination of critical discourse is the necessity of abandoning its venues. He withholds the full disclosure of this aspect of his thesis until the final pages of the book, so one is tempted to read the end as an act of disappearance, a repudiation eloquently resonating in the silence or aftermath of //The Theory-Death of the Avant-Garde//. (But then, Mann troublingly reappears in the pages of //Contemporary Literature// reviewing further episodes of the avant-garde; which suggests that an interminable discourse on termination is not so easily disavowed for one whose sensibility and training have been nurtured for precisely such tasks.) We&amp;#39;re left with the implication that the traditional avant-garde must, once again, lead the way; that exemplary nonproductive acts of disappearance must be pioneered by artists.(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) __“Without exception __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__art that calls itself art,__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)__ that is registered as art, that circulates within art contexts __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__can never__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)again(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__pose as anything but systems-maintenance__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)__.” Nor does Mann expect staged repudiations, melodramatic scenarios in which the artist says__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %), in effect,(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) __I despise you all__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %)and will no longer give you the satisfaction of opposing me (or siding with me):(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__I no longer play the game. Nor will it be a Duchampian withdrawal without theatrics or denunciation. Instead what is required is to have never entered the lists in the first place__.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) “What one must imagine is an unprecedented silence, exile, and cunning. …(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__Not a critical theater in which to represent oneself but a hidden struggle to dismantle in oneself__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %), in one&amp;#39;s network,(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)__the entire theatrical apparatus__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;font-family:Calibri&amp;#34; %). A fast for burning off discursive toxins.” The Artist, setting the pace for critics, disappears like Conchis in //The Magus// or Slothrop in //Gravity&amp;#39;s Rainbow//(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Calibri&amp;#34; %).&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
