(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNoSpacing&amp;#34; %)
**It&amp;#39;s a prereq to debate.**

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
**Shively, 2000 **Ruth Lessl Shively, Associate Professor of Political Science, Texas AandM, POLITICAL THEORY AND PARTISAN POLITICS, 2000, p. 181-2. (DRGNS/E614)

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 6pt; line-height: 115%; &amp;#34; %)The requirements given thus far are primarily negative. The (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%; background:fuchsia;mso-highlight:fuchsia&amp;#34; %)ambiguists(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 6pt; line-height: 115%; background-color: fuchsia; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 6pt; line-height: 115%; &amp;#34; %)must say &amp;#34;no&amp;#34; to—they must reject and limit—some ideas and actions. In what follows, we will also find that they (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%; background:fuchsia;mso-highlight:fuchsia&amp;#34; %)must say &amp;#34;yes&amp;#34; to(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 6pt; line-height: 115%; background-color: fuchsia; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 6pt; line-height: 115%; &amp;#34; %)some things. In particular, they must say &amp;#34;yes&amp;#34; to the idea of (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%;background:fuchsia;mso-highlight:fuchsia&amp;#34; %)rational persuasion(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 6pt; line-height: 115%; &amp;#34; %). This means, first, that (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%; background:fuchsia;mso-highlight:fuchsia&amp;#34; %)they must recognize the role of agreement in political contest, or the basic accord that is necessary to discord(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 6pt; line-height: 115%; &amp;#34; %). The mistake that the ambiguists make here is a common one. The mistake is in thinking that agreement marks the end of contest—that consensus kills debate. But this is true only if the agreement is perfect—if there is nothing at all left to question or contest. In most cases, however, our agreements are highly imperfect. We agree on some matters but not on others, on generalities but not on specifics, on principles but not on their applications, and so on. And (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%; background:fuchsia;mso-highlight:fuchsia&amp;#34; %)this(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 6pt; line-height: 115%; background-color: fuchsia; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 6pt; line-height: 115%; &amp;#34; %)kind of limited (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;background:fuchsia;mso-highlight:fuchsia&amp;#34; %)agreement is the starting(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 6pt; line-height: 115%; background-color: fuchsia; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %)** **(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%; background:fuchsia;mso-highlight:fuchsia&amp;#34; %)condition of contest and debate(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 6pt; line-height: 115%; &amp;#34; %). As John Courtney Murray writes: We hold certain truths; therefore we can argue about them. It seems to have been one of the corruptions of intelligence by positivism to assume that argument ends when agreement is reached. In a basic sense, the reverse is true. There **can be no argument except on the premise, and within a context, of agreement**. (Murray 1960, 10) In other words, we cannot argue about something if we are not communicating: if we cannot agree on the topic and terms of argument or if we have utterly different ideas about what counts as evidence or good argument. At the very least, we must agree about what it is that is being debated before we can debate it. For instance**, **(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11.0pt;line-height:115%;background:fuchsia;mso-highlight:fuchsia&amp;#34; %)one cannot have an argument about euthanasia with someone who thinks euthanasia is a musical group(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 6pt; line-height: 115%; &amp;#34; %)**.** One cannot successfully stage a sit-in if one&amp;#39;s target audience simply thinks everyone is resting or if those doing the sitting have no complaints. Nor can one demonstrate resistance to a policy if no one knows that it is a policy. In other words, contest is meaningless if there is a lack of agreement or communication about what is being contested. Resisters, demonstrators, and debaters must have some shared ideas about the subject and/or the terms of their disagreements. The participants and the target of a sit-in must share an understanding of the complaint at hand. And a demonstrator&amp;#39;s audience must know what is being resisted. In short, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;background:fuchsia;mso-highlight:fuchsia&amp;#34; %)the contesting of an idea presumes some agreement about what that idea is(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 6pt; line-height: 115%; background-color: fuchsia; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 6pt; line-height: 115%; &amp;#34; %)and how one might go about intelligibly contesting it. In other words, contestation rests on some basic agreement or harmony.

=== 2 ===

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Their aff participates in economic exchange, hoping that the pendulum that is the global economy swings their direction. This never acknowledges that this system of transnational capitalism is what made human lives in Africa less valuble than the profit of natural gas sold in america, and allows us to liquidate the world down to its exchange value.

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Baudrillard 93(%%) jean, frenchie French man, transparency of evil ,p 8 – 11

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Thus (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)every individual category is subject to contamination, substitution is possible(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) between any sphere and any other: there is a total confusion of types(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %). Sex is no longer located in sex itself, but elsewhere - everywhere else, in fact. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Politics is no longer restricted to the political sphere, but infects every sphere -(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) economics, science, art, sport . . . Sport itself, meanwhile, is no longer located in sport as such, but instead in business, in sex, in politics, in the general style of performance. These domains are affected by sport&amp;#39;s criteria of  &amp;#39;excellence&amp;#39;, effort and record-breaking as by its childish notion of self-transcendence. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)Each category (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)thus (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)passes through a phase transition during which its essence is diluted in homeopathic doses(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %), infinitesimal relative to the total solution, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)until it finally disappears, leaving a trace so small as to be indiscernible,(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) like the &amp;#39;memory of water&amp;#39;(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %). AIDS is the reflection not so much of an excess of sex or sexual pleasure as of sex&amp;#39;s decompensation through its general spread into all areas of life, its venting through all the trivial variants of sexual incantation. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)The real loss of immunity concerns sex as a whole, with the disappearance of sexual difference and hence of sexualitv per se.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) It is in this diffraction of the sexual reality (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; color: rgb(6, 6, 6)&amp;#34; %)AFTERTHEORGY principle, at the fractal, micrological and non-human level, that the essential confusion of the epidemic takes hold. Perhaps we still have a memory of sex, rather as water &amp;#39;remembers&amp;#39; molecules no matter how diluted. But that is the whole point: this is only a molecular memory, the corpuscular memory of an earlier life, and not a memory of forms or singularities (water, after all, can hardly retain the features of a face, or the colour of someone&amp;#39;s eyes). (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)so what we are left with is the simple imprint of a faceless sexuality infinitely watered down in a broth of politics, media and communications, and eventually manifested in the viral explosion of AIDS. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)The law that is imposed on us is the law of the confusion of categories. Everything is sexual. Everything is political. Everything is aesthetic. All at once. Everything has acquired a political meaning(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;color:#060606&amp;#34; %), especially since 1968; (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)and it is not just everyday life but also madness, language, the media, even desire, that are politicized as they enter the sphere of liberation(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %),(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;color:#060606&amp;#34; %) the sphere of mass processes(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %). Likewise everything has become sexual, anything can be an object of desire: power, knowledge - everything is interpreted in terms of phantasies, in terms of repression, and sexual stereotypy reigns in every last corner.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;color:#060606&amp;#34; %) Likewise, too, everything is now aestheticized(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %): politics is aestheticized in the spectacle, sex in advertising and porn, and all kinds of activity in what is conventionally referred to as culture - a sort of all-pervasive media- and advertising-led semiologization:(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;color:#060606&amp;#34; %) &amp;#39;culture degree Xerox&amp;#39;. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Each category is generalized to the greatest possible extent, so that it eventually loses all specificity and is reabsorbed by all the other categories. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)When everything is political, nothing is political any more(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %),(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;color:#060606&amp;#34; %) the word itself is meaningless. when everything is sexual, nothing is sexual any more, and sex loses its deterr,ninants. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)When everything is aesthetic, nothing is beautiful or ugly any more, and art itself disappears. This paradoxical state of affairs, which is simultaneously the complete actualization of an idea(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %), the perfect realization of the whole tendency of modernity, and the negation of that idea and that tendency, thei(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;color:#060606&amp;#34; %)r (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)annihilation by virtue of their very success(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %), by virtue of their extension beyond their own bounds (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)- this state of affairs is epitomized by a single figure: the transpolitical, the transsexual, the transaesthetic. There is no longer an avant-garde, political, sexual or artistic, embodying a capacity for anticipation; hence the possibility of any radical critique -(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) whether in the name of desire, of revolution, or of the liberation of forms - (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)no longer exists. The days of that revolutionary movement are gone.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)The glorious march of modernity has not led to the transformation of all values,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)as we once dreamed it would, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)but instead to a dispersal and involution of value whose upshot for us is total confusio(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)n - the impossibility of apprehending any determining principle, whether of an aesthetic, a sexual or a political kind(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %). The proletariat has not succeeded in negating itself as such - the century and a half since Marx has made that clear. The proletariat has failed to negate ltseIf qua class and thereby abolish class society per se. Perhaps this is because the proletariat never was a class, as had been supposed - because only the bourgeoisie was a true class, and therefore the only one capable of negating itself as such. For it has indeed negated itself, along with capital, and so generated a classless society, albeit one which has nothing to do with the classless society that was supposed to arise from a revolution and from a negation of the proletariat as such. As for the proletariat, it has simply disappeared - vanished along with the class struggle itself. There can be no doubt that had capitalism developed in accordance with its own contradictory logic, it would have been defeated by the proletariat. In an ideal sense, Matx&amp;#39;s analysis is still irreproachable. But Marx simply did not foresee that it would be possible for capital, in the face of the imminent threat to its existence, to transpoliticize itself, as it were: to launch itself into an orbit beyond the relations of production and political contradictions, to make itself autonomous in a free-floating, ecstatic and haphazardforrn, and thus to totalize the world in its own image. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)Capital(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) (if it may still be so called) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)has barred the way of political economy and the law of value; it is in this sense that it has successfully escaped its own end. Henceforward it can function independently of its own former aims, and absolutely without reference to any aims whatsoever.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 11.0pt;line-height:115%;color:#101010;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)The inaugural event of this mutation was undoubtedly the Great Crash of 1929; the stockmarket crisis of 1987 was merely an aftershock.

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)In the way that politics is dead, the market is also dead, and it its current existence speculations on speculations, abstracted to the nth degree from any basis in reality. Sure, economic crisises come up, but only as the preventative electroshocks that show us things could be so much worse if we were to seriously upset the global balance of power and exchange of commodity. The aff is part and parcel of this system of global deterrence that lets small states and small markets fail in order to maintain a larger fiction about money meaning something.

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Baudrillard 95(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)jean, way cooler now that he’s underground, “The Gulf War Never Happened”, Translated by Paul Patton, Indiana University Press, p. 83-4

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; line-height: 115%; &amp;#34; %) 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)A variant on Clausewitz: non-war is the absence of politics pursued by other means ... It no longer proceeds from a political will to dominate or from a vital impulsion or an antagonistic violence, but from the will to impose a general consensus by deterrence. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)This(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %) consensual violence can be as deadly as conflictual violence, but its aim is to overcome any hegemonic rivalry(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %), even when cold and balanced by terror, as it has been over the last forty years. It was already at work in all the democracies taken one by one; (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)it operates today on a global level which is conceived as an immense democracy governed by a homogeneous order which has as its emblem the UN and the Rights of Man. The Gulf War is the first consensual war, the first war conducted legally and globally with a view to (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)putting an end to war and liquidating any confrontation likely to threaten the (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)hence forward (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)unified system of control(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %). This (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)was(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) already (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)the aim of dualistic(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) (East and West) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)deterrence(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %);(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) today we pass to the monopolistic stage under the aegis of American power. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Logically, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)this democratic and consensual form should be able to dispense with war, but it will no doubt continue to have local and episodic need of it(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;background: lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %).(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) The Gulf War is one of these transitive episodes. hesitating for this reason between hard and soft forms: virtual war or real war? But (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)the balance is in the process of definitively inclining in one direction, and tomorrow there will be nothing but the virtual violence of consensus(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %), the simultaneity in real time of the global consensus: this will happen tomorrow and it will be the beginning of a world with no tomorrow. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Electronic (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)war (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)no longer has any political objective strictly speaking: it (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)functions as a preventative electroshock against any future conflict.(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) Just as in modern communication there is no longer any interlocutor, so in this electronic war there is no longer any enemy. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)there is only a refractory element which must be neutralised and consensualised(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %). (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)This is what the Americans seek to do, these missionary people bearing electroshocks which will shepherd everybody towards democracy.(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) It is therefore pointless to question the political aims of this war: (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)the only (transpolitical) aim is to align everybody with the global lowest common denominator. the democratic denominator(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)(which, in its extension, approaches ever closer to the degree zero of politics). The lowest common multiplier being information in all its (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)forms, which, as it extends towards infinity, also approaches ever closer to the degree zero of its content. In this sense(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %).(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) consensus as the degree zero of democracy and information as the degree zero of opinion are in total affinity: the New World Order will be both consensual and televisual(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %). That is indeed why the targeted bombings carefully avoided the Iraqi television antennae (which stand out like a sore thumb in the sky over Baghdad). War is no lbnger what it used to be ...

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:Calibri;mso-ascii-theme-font: major-latin;mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;ＭＳ ゴシック~&amp;#34;;mso-fareast-theme-font:major-fareast; mso-hansi-theme-font:major-latin;mso-bidi-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;; mso-bidi-theme-font:major-bidi;mso-bidi-font-weight:bold&amp;#34; %)This financial speculation will eventually run its course and collapse itself; this is our only way out of this rigged game, to accelerate speculation past a point of use value, and to a point where this financial system literally collapses.

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Fernando(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %), Jeremy, Jean Baudrillard Fellow at the European Graduate School and Fellow of Tembusu College at The National University of Singapore. He received his MA in Media Philosophy from the European Graduate School (2006) and an MA in English Literature from Nanyang Technological University (2008). “Waking up with Obama; or the morning after ...”, February 10, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)2010(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %), http:~/~/www.jeremyfernando.com/art_12.html

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)The logic of &amp;#34;all under one idea&amp;#34; is terror , for what is captured is the space of public opinion. As Jean-François Lyotard and Jean-Loup Thébaud never let us forget, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)terror is &amp;#34;a blow that is not struck on the adversary but it is hoped that the blow will be borne by the third party, the witness.&amp;#34;2 The events of September 11 were terroristic, not because two planes crashed into the World Trade Center in New York City, but because we are no longer allowed to read that date in any other way. The fact that the year, 2001, no longer has to be mentioned, suggests that every other year has been sucked into it, has already been effaced. What has been taken hostage is the ability to negotiate, the ability for thought. (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)As Lyotard and Thébaud continue, &amp;#34;Whereas in a two-sided battle, my opponent thinks that what I think and do is unjust, and I think that what he does and thinks is unjust. Well, his freedom is complete and so is mine. With a hostage, I am applying . . . not even &amp;#34;pressure.&amp;#34; It is much more than that. It is the social bond taken as a fact of nature.&amp;#34;3 What has been taken away is choice: one no longer can do anything but constitute &amp;#34;September 11&amp;#34; as a &amp;#34;terror attack on the United States &amp;#34;; your only other option, alternative, is to refuse this interpretation. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)This is hardly a space for negotiation—all you can say is &amp;#34;yes&amp;#34; or &amp;#34;no.&amp;#34; Here, one can hear an echo of the Obama rally cry—&amp;#34;yes we can.&amp;#34;(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) Most of the focus has been on the emphasis of the affirmation that &amp;#34;we can.&amp;#34; However what has been driven aside—rather forcefully at that—is the notion of the &amp;#34;no&amp;#34;; what seems to have been discounted completely is the choice to not do something, even though one can. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)This suggests that a(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)ll potentiality has to be translated into actuality;(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) in other words, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)potentiality is only a phase before actuality(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)—if this particular translation is not made, there might as well have been none to begin with. But as Giorgio Agamben has taught us, potentiality as such always already brings with it the potentiality not-to-be. Hence, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)the implication of this call is that only results matter—by extension, you are only as good as your productivity, as what you produce(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %); &amp;#34;you as such do not matter, unless you can.&amp;#34; Clearly in the Obama world, there would be no place for Bartleby.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) When Barack Obama said, &amp;#34;for we know that our patchwork heritage is a strength, not a weakness. We are a nation of Christians and Muslims, Jews and Hindus, and nonbelievers. We are shaped by every language and culture, drawn from every end of this Earth,&amp;#34; he was met with thunderous applause, for this sounds like a reiteration of the American Dream, where regardless of race, language, or religion, anyone has a chance of success. In many ways, he is the very embodiment of this philosophy of meritocracy: the entire Obama campaign was run on the premise that Americans should vote for him not as a black man, but as the most competent candidate, the one that met all the conditions to be the leader. However, this also reiterates the fact that &amp;#34;as long as you fulfill the set criteria, you will be rewarded.&amp;#34; It is precisely this understanding—the knowledge that power rests in forms—that Barack Obama possesses. This is why anyone and everyone can gain recognition under the new regime: (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)no longer is the banal binary of &amp;#34;you are either with us or against us&amp;#34; at play; instead we are now faced with the far more insidious challenge of the &amp;#34;patchwork.&amp;#34; On the surface, it would seem that a patchwork is fluid and welcoming to all differences. However, anyone who has done any sewing would know that patchworks run on strict logics: anything that does not fall within the overall scheme is cut out and thrown away. In this &amp;#34;patchwork&amp;#34; world that Obama is invoking, every American—and since he never lets the rest of the world forget that the US &amp;#34;remains the most prosperous, powerful nation on Earth&amp;#34;—by extension (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)everyone in the world, is now a unit for exchange; a calculable entity which has to choose between fitting the master-plan or being cut out.(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) You are no longer even given the choice to be &amp;#34;against us,&amp;#34; to resist, for (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)if you are assimilated, you no longer even exist(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %). In this sense, one is no longer allowed to be the enemy; the only option that remains is to either play (unconditionally accepting the rules of the game) or leave. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)This is(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) of course nothing more than (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)capitalism at its purest: everything is equal, flattened(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)—channeling the spectre of Jean Baudrillard, everything has been &amp;#34;(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)liberated so that it can enter a state of pure circulation, so that it can go into orbit(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %),&amp;#34;4 (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)in the(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) precise (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)sense that everyone and everything is completely and utterly exchangeable.(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) However, it is not as if this complete exchangeability comes without a price. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)If everything is equivalent to everything else, this also means that nothing is inherent any longer;(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) t(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)here are no longer any secrets, any unknowns. Everything is completely and utterly knowable, calculable, disseminable. And as Baudrillard has warned us time and time again, when &amp;#34;each individual category is subject to contamination, substitution is possible between any sphere and any other: there is total confusion of types. . . . Each category is generalized to the greatest possible extent, so that it eventually loses all specificity and is reabsorbed by all the other categories.&amp;#34;5 In other words, it can be found everywhere; and by extension, nowhere at exactly the same time(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %). (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)If everything is political, then politics itself is meaningless; if economics is everything, the economy as such ceases to have any meaning(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %). In terms of humans, if we are all exactly the same as the next person, this means that none of us are singular(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %).(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Perhaps this was already apparent by the increasing importance of &amp;#34;human resource management&amp;#34; over the last few decades: by this logic, humans are nothing more than resources; constantly depreciating, and more importantly, completely replaceable. Here we find ourselves in an almost Beckettian situation; one where we can no longer go on (after all what is the point), but have to at the same time. Perhaps (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)at this point (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)we have to attempt to find hope in the perfection of the system itself, in the fact that no system can be perfect, in the fact that the absolute perfection of the system is its own failing point.(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)The only way to face this absurd premise (where perfection and imperfection are exactly the same) is to be completely ironic; not in the traditional sense of keeping a distance from it (the distance of analysis) but the very opposite—the absurd position of utterly plunging into the very absurdity itself. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)When faced with an utterly indifferent system—governed(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 11.0pt;line-height:115%;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)by a single Idea without any regard for the followers of that Idea—one has no choice but to be even more indifferent.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) For this is the nightmare of any disciplinary mechanism: what power would it have over the subject if the subject did not mind being disciplined in the first place? In this sense, not only is resistance to the disciplining expected, it is absolutely required: one can even go so far as to say that resistance is the very crux of the disciplinary mechanism. Without this assumption, the entire disciplinary system would collapse on itself. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)When faced with a system that attempts to objectify (to flatten everyone into variations of each other), instead of resisting—insisting on our subjectivity and uniqueness—(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)we must take the plunge and embrace our status as pure object(s).(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) The Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) is an apt metaphor for this: it spreads, not by combating the defenses of the host, but by doing the exact opposite; HIV attaches itself to its host precisely by using the host&amp;#39;s defenses. In this manner, the more the host body attempts to defend itself, the more it attempts to combat the HIV, the more the virus spreads(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %). In this sense, a position of hyper-conformity may potentially short-circuit the entire logic. Capitalism—and economics as a whole—is hinged on the fact that its subjects attach personal meaning to their consumption. Thus (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)we must abandon the age old strategy of &amp;#34;finding meaning&amp;#34; in our own lives. By plunging ourselves into infinite circulation,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) by embracing utter and absolute meaninglessness, we will not face up to capitalism, but instead take it on its own terms(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Forget revolutions: they move around in circles and eventually end up in the same place.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) In the Year of the Ox, we must embrace the fact that we are castrated beings, all lined up and facing the same direction. Perhaps even embracing the ironic advantage of being a slave—remembering always Georges Bataille&amp;#39;s teaching that slaves cannot be sacrificed. After all, why must we read &amp;#34;yes we can&amp;#34; as a strong affirmation—it can also be a question, an empty claim, or even better, a plea; soft, weak, whimpering.6 And perhaps, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)in this absolute indifference, not just to the system, but to ourselves, we might be able to seduce the totalizing logic of capitalism itself(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;background: lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) Thus, we offer it the challenge of our own emptiness, our own absence, in fact, our own deaths. Perhaps it might respond with its own …

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) 

=== 3 ===

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
The USFG should base the value of our currency on the TI-89 series of calculators

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

=== Case ===

==== Natural Gas Prices low now, there is prime opportunity to keep the price low ====

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Richard Thompson 2012(%%) reporter, New Orleans Times-Picayune

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(Low natural gas prices may draw industries to Louisiana, http:~/~/www.nola.com/business/index.ssf/2012/07/low_natural_gas_prices_may_dra.html)

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%;background:aqua;mso-highlight:aqua&amp;#34; %)With natural gas at decade-low prices, state economic officials are working to catch a wave of new investment interest from industries eager to tap into the abundant supply of the clean-burning fuel to power their plants(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;background: aqua;mso-highlight:aqua&amp;#34; %).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)&amp;#34;We&amp;#39;re working hard to position ourselves to get a disproportionate share of that new activity(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %),&amp;#34; Stephen Moret, secretary of Louisiana Economic Development, said in an interview last week. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;background:aqua;mso-highlight:aqua&amp;#34; %)A wellspring of inexpensive natural gas has helped drive down electricity rates for some industrial users,(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) particularly those in the chemical industry(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %). (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Competitive fuel prices have already been at least partially responsible for several new industrial project(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)s in the state, including a new natural gas-fired power plant Entergy Louisiana plans to build in Westwego and a methanol plant that Vancouver-based Methanex Corp. may build in Geismar. Royal Dutch Shell PLC is reportedly considering building a $10 billion gas-to-diesel processing plant in Louisiana. That plant, still years away from reality, would convert enough natural gas into diesel fuel to fill more than 160,000 cars a day.

==== We haven’t reached a peak in Natural Gas, new techniques and new wells are fruitful ====

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Nolan Hart 2010(%%) Energy Industry, self employed. To pay the bills I work in the oil and gas industry, on drilling rigs in a technical position related to directional drilling (http:~/~/doodlebugs.xomba.com/how_long_until_peak_natural_gas. Author of works in Horizontal drilling industry and blogs about the energy industry)

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)What About Peak Natural Gas? So, does that mean a peak in natural gas too? After all both are fossil fuels and both come from wells, often from the same well in some areas. In the past prices of natural gas and oil moved in unison. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;background:aqua;mso-highlight:aqua&amp;#34; %)The natural gas paradox is this: In the past decade a technology called horizontal drilling was perfected and now shale rock, which was never before seen as a reservoir of natural gas or oil, is being exploited all across the country. This revolution is going full swing in the U(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)nited (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: aqua; mso-highlight: aqua&amp;#34; %)S(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)tates with areas like the vast Marcellus shale in the Northeast and the Haynesville shale in Louisiana, proving to hold trillions of cubic feet of natural gas. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: aqua; mso-highlight: aqua&amp;#34; %)Even the die hard prophets of peak oil doom are finally waking up to the fact that we have many more years worth of this resource left.(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) We suddenly have over a one hundred year supply of natural gas at current consumption rates and that number has been growing by about one decade more each year since 2005. (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;ＭＳ ゴシック~&amp;#34;; mso-fareast-theme-font:major-fareast;background:aqua;mso-highlight:aqua&amp;#34; %)//New discoveries such as the Eagle Ford shale in south Texas are adding trillions more cubic feet to the natural gas inventory. So, peak oil, yes. Peak natural gas, no way. Shale Everywhere//(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %), (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)A Worldwide Glut Of Natural Gas Coming By the way, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)those shale beds that are full of natural gas don&amp;#39;t just exist here. There are dozens of such areas around the world. (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%; mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;ＭＳ ゴシック~&amp;#34;;mso-fareast-theme-font:major-fareast; background:aqua;mso-highlight:aqua&amp;#34; %)//Only because the U.S. pioneered horizontal drilling has the majority of drilling been done here. As we begin to export horizontal drilling to China, Australia and Western Europe, the worldwide glut of natural gas supply will only get bigger.//

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

==== There is no real way of predicting what is going to happen if LNG exportation comes through – there is too much risk in adopting an LNG export policy ====

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Michael Levi 2012(%%) David M. Rubenstein Senior Fellow for Energy and the Environment at the Council on Foreign Relations (CFR), where he is also director of its Program on Energy Security and Climate Change

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(The Hamilton Project, A strategy for U.S. Natural Gas Exports June 2012 http:~~/~~/www.brookings.edu/~~~~/media/research/files/papers/2012/6/13%20exports%20levi/06_exports_leviurl:http://www.brookings.edu/~~/media/research/files/papers/2012/6/13%20exports%20levi/06_exports_levi)

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)The first way that prices could converge is through U.S. LNG exports, which could ultimately bring the various prices together, net of transport costs (including an indeterminate risk premium paid to investors in risky LNG projects). Indeed initial natural gas exports themselves will tend to shrink opportunities for subsequent exports. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%; background:aqua;mso-highlight:aqua&amp;#34; %)A recent DOE study projects that with moderate U.S. gas resources and twelve billion cubic feet a day of exports, U.S. benchmark prices would rise to more than $8 per thousand cubic feet by the middle of the next decade(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) (EIA 2012c). (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;background:aqua;mso-highlight:aqua&amp;#34; %)When combined with the cost of moving natural gas from the U(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)nited (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: aqua; mso-highlight: aqua&amp;#34; %)S(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)tates to overseas markets, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: aqua; mso-highlight: aqua&amp;#34; %)there is a strong chance that some exports would be unprofitable at that price.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;background: aqua;mso-highlight:aqua&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;background:aqua;mso-highlight:aqua&amp;#34; %)The same analysis found that if U.S. resources were lower than anticipated, prices could reach $14 per(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) thousand cubic feet by 2020, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: aqua; mso-highlight: aqua&amp;#34; %)making exports undoubtedly uneconomic at the margin(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %). All that said, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)assuming U.S. LNG exports at the outset of this analysis would make no sense, since their very existence depends on the particular export policy that is adopted.

==== Smooth transitions fail – technological overshoot impossible to overcome, the aff will fail ====

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Samuel Alexander 2012(%%) lecturer at the Office for Environmental Programs, University of Melbourne, Australia, and editor of Voluntary Simplicity Ted Trainer and the Simpler Way, Simplicity Institute Report 12d, 2012  http:~~/~~/simplicityinstitute.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/TedTrainerandTheSimplerWay1.pdfurl:http://simplicityinstitute.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/TedTrainerandTheSimplerWay1.pdf%5D)

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%;font-family:Cambria;mso-bidi-font-family:Cambria&amp;#34; %)Trainer’s general point on technology (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;background:aqua;mso-highlight:aqua&amp;#34; %)is that the extent of ecological overshoot is already so great that technology will never be able to solve the ecological crises of our age, certainly not in a world based on economic growth and with a growing global population(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family: Cambria;mso-bidi-font-family:Cambria&amp;#34; %). Amory (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Lovins(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family: Cambria;mso-bidi-font-family:Cambria&amp;#34; %) (1998) is probably the best~-~-‐(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)known advocate of technological solutions to ecological problems, most famous for his ‘factor four’ thesis(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 11.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:Cambria;mso-bidi-font-family:Cambria&amp;#34; %). He (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)argues that (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: aqua; mso-highlight: aqua&amp;#34; %)if we exploit technology we could have four times the economic output without increasing environmental impact(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) (or maintain current economic output and reduce environmental impact by a factor of four(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:Cambria;mso-bidi-font-family: Cambria&amp;#34; %)). (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)But as we have already seen, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: aqua; mso-highlight: aqua&amp;#34; %)if the rich world continues to grow at 3% per year until 2070 and by that stage the poorest nations have attained similarly high living standards(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) – which is the aim of the global development agenda – total world economic output (and impact) could well be as much as 60 times larger than it is today.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%;font-family:Cambria;mso-bidi-font-family:Cambria&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)If we assume that sustainability requires that fossil fuel use and other resource consumption must be half of what they are today (and the greenhouse problem would require a larger reduction than this), then what is needed is something like a factor 120 reduction in the per unit impact of GDP, not merely a factor 4 reduction(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%;font-family:Cambria;mso-bidi-font-family:Cambria&amp;#34; %) (Trainer, 2007: 117). Again, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)even allowing for some uncertainty in these calculations, (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height: 115%;mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;ＭＳ ゴシック~&amp;#34;;mso-fareast-theme-font:major-fareast; background:aqua;mso-highlight:aqua&amp;#34; %)//the claim that technological solutions can solve the ecological crises and sustain the growth paradigm is simply not credible//(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 11.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:Cambria;mso-bidi-font-family:Cambria&amp;#34; %) Trainer has shown that (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)the absolute decoupling necessary is just beyond what is remotely possible. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: aqua; mso-highlight: aqua&amp;#34; %)The final nail in the coffin of techno~-~-‐ optimists is the fact that despite decades of extraordinary technological advance, the overall ecological impact of the global economy is still increasing(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family: Cambria;mso-bidi-font-family:Cambria&amp;#34; %) (Jackson, 2009: Ch. 4), making even a factor four reduction through technological advance seem wildly optimistic.

==== Environmental racism is too narrow a focus.  3 impacts: they disregard structural racism, can&amp;#39;t understand how racism becomes pervasive in defining space and reincorporate racism into society.  Turns case. ====

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Laura Pulido.  “Rethinking Environmental Racism: White Privilege and Urban Development in Southern California”.  Annals of the Association of American Geographers 90(1), 12-40.  2000.  Wiley-Blackwell Publishing.  Accessed from: (% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%;color:windowtext&amp;#34; %)www.praxis-epress.org/CGR/30-Pulido.pdfurl:http://www.praxis-epress.org/CGR/30-Pulido.pdf(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) – M.E.

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; line-height: 115%; &amp;#34; %)Although the study of racial inequality is not new to geographers (Anderson, 1987; Gilmore, 1998; Jackson and Penrose, 1994; Kobayashi and Peake, 1994; S. Smith, 1993; Woods, 1998), environmental racism offers us new insights into the subject, particularly its spatiality. Unfortunately, (% style=&amp;#34;background-color: yellow; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %)**__scholars of environmental racism have not seriously problematized racism, opting instead for a de facto conception based on malicious, individual acts.__**(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; line-height: 115%; &amp;#34; %)There are several problems with this approach. First,(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow&amp;#34; %)**__by reducing racism to a hostile, discriminatory act,__**(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; line-height: 115%; &amp;#34; %)many(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow&amp;#34; %)**__researchers__**(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; line-height: 115%; &amp;#34; %), with the notable exception of(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; line-height: 115%; &amp;#34; %)Bullard (1990), (% style=&amp;#34;background-color: yellow; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %)**__miss the role of structural and hegemonic forms of racism in contributing to such inequalities.__**(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; line-height: 115%; &amp;#34; %) Indeed, structural racism has been the dominant mode of analysis in other substantive areas of social research, such as residential segregation (Massey and Denton, 1993) and employment patterns (Kirschenman and Neckerman, 1991), since at least Myrdal’s An American Dilemma (1944). Not only has the (% style=&amp;#34;background-color: yellow; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %)**__environmental racism literature become estranged from social science discussions of race,__**(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; line-height: 115%; &amp;#34; %)but, in the case of urban-based research,(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow&amp;#34; %)**__it is divorced from contemporary urban geography.__**(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; line-height: 115%; &amp;#34; %)A second and related concern is that racism is not conceptualized as the dynamic sociospatial process that it is. (% style=&amp;#34;background-color: yellow; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %)**__Because racism is understood as a discrete act that may be spatially expressed, it is not seen as a sociospatial relation both constitutive of the city and produced by it. As a result, the spatiality of racism is not understood, particularly the relationship between places. __**(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; line-height: 115%; &amp;#34; %)Yet(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background: yellow&amp;#34; %)**__pollution concentrations are inevitably the product of relationships between distinct places,__**(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; line-height: 115%; &amp;#34; %) including industrial zones, affluent suburbs, working-class suburbs, and downtown areas, all of which are racialized. (% style=&amp;#34;background-color: yellow; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %)**__A final problem with a narrow understanding of racism is that it limits claims, thereby reproducing a racist social order. By defining racism so narrowly, racial inequalities that cannot be attributed directly to a hostile, discriminatory act are not acknowledged as such,__**(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; line-height: 115%; &amp;#34; %)but perhaps as evidence of individual deficiencies or choices. Yet(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow&amp;#34; %)**__if we wish to create a more just society, we must acknowledge the breadth and depth of racism.__**

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;background-color: yellow; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; text-decoration: none&amp;#34; %)**__ __**

==== Impact Takeout – No risk of an impact.  Environmental racism isn&amp;#39;t happening now.  Studies prove. ====

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Glasgow 5 (Joshua, Yale Law School JD candidate, Buffalo Environmental Law Journal, 13 Buff. Envt’l L.J. 69, Fall, ln).

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 9pt; line-height: 115%; &amp;#34; %) 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; line-height: 115%; &amp;#34; %)In addition to courtroom difficulties, (% style=&amp;#34;background-color: yellow; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %)**__the environmental justice movement was challenged by a number of studies __**(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; line-height: 115%; &amp;#34; %)in the mid-1990s challenging the evidence of discriminatory siting and exposure. *76(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow&amp;#34; %)**__An __**(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; line-height: 115%; &amp;#34; %)influential(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow&amp;#34; %)**__University of Massachusetts study__**(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; line-height: 115%; &amp;#34; %)conducted in 1994 examined over five hundred hazardous waste facilities and(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow&amp;#34; %)**__found no evidence of discriminatory siting. __**(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; line-height: 115%; &amp;#34; %)27 Additionally,(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow&amp;#34; %)**__scholars challenged the__**(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; line-height: 115%; &amp;#34; %)earlier studies&amp;#39; (% style=&amp;#34;background-color: yellow; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %)**__methodologies, including the sample selection, the definition of minority, the geographic scope examined, and the failure to control for other variables.__**(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; line-height: 115%; &amp;#34; %) 28 In a series of articles, Vicki Been set forth a particularly powerful critique of environmental justice studies. 29 Been notes that most studies examined the contemporary makeup of a neighborhood impacted by a LULU, not its makeup at the time of siting. 30 (% style=&amp;#34;background-color: yellow; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; &amp;#34; %)**__This method ignores the possibility that a LULU would lower nearby housing prices, causing affluent residents to move away.__**(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; line-height: 115%; &amp;#34; %)These residents would be replaced by lower-income individuals, attracted by the lower housing prices. As a result of these market dynamics, even LULUs located in a wealthy neighborhood could later become surrounded by the poor. 31 2.(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow&amp;#34; %)**__This &amp;#34;chicken-or-the-egg&amp;#34; dilemma has plagued the environmental justice literature. 32__**

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;background-color: yellow; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial; text-decoration: none&amp;#34; %)**__ __**

(% class=&amp;#34;tag&amp;#34; %)
Reconceptualizing democracy traps us in false hope.

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)** **

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;cite&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Baudrillard 2008(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height:115%;mso-bidi-font-weight: bold&amp;#34; %)(Jean, Interviewed by Philippe Petit.  Present Considerations: The Uncertainty of All Value Systems.  International Journal of Baudrillard Studies, Volume 5, Number 1 (January, 2008).)

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:9.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)**Petit**(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:9.0pt;line-height: 115%&amp;#34; %): //Listening to you, that destiny seems inescapable. It&amp;#39;s no use asking what you think of those who are intent on refounding democratic citizenship.//(%%)
  
 **Baudrillard**: __At the current time, (% style=&amp;#34;background:aqua; mso-highlight:aqua&amp;#34; %)democracy is a social form that&amp;#39;s about as ancestral as (%%)the (% style=&amp;#34;background:aqua;mso-highlight:aqua&amp;#34; %)symbolic exchange (%%)of primitive societies. And (% style=&amp;#34;background:aqua;mso-highlight:aqua&amp;#34; %)we dream of it in the same way(%%). (% style=&amp;#34;background:aqua;mso-highlight: aqua&amp;#34; %)The political (%%)in general (% style=&amp;#34;background:aqua;mso-highlight: aqua&amp;#34; %)continues to be the waking dream of Western societies (%%)– of the exoteric societies where everything is expressed by technics. The esoteric societies, for their part (whether they are disinherited or traditional societies), long since brought politics into line with tribal arrangements. (% style=&amp;#34;background:aqua;mso-highlight:aqua&amp;#34; %)They have trapped and tamed the Western machinery of politics, law, democracy and the universal in their per­sonal structures and relations; they have integrated linearity and history into their own cycle(%%).__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:9.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)We may ask ourselves whether, on a much vaster scale and by the roundabout route of rationality, it isn&amp;#39;t the same with our Western societies. Doesn&amp;#39;t the political sphere obey impulses, obligations, challenges and fantasies that have lit­tle to do with public affairs? This incorruptible truth of evil, of the irrational, shows through in the very corruption of the political, which must therefore be interpreted positively as the impossibility of Political Reason realizing itself. This is what explains why the more imperative transparency becomes, the greater the corrup­tion. By wishing merely to take into account a politically correct human nature ­a fundamentally Rousseauist vision – (% style=&amp;#34;background:aqua;mso-highlight:aqua&amp;#34; %)__the militants of the good democratic cause __(%%)__– of those who, more subtly, wish to rehabilitate the “essence” of the political – (% style=&amp;#34;background:aqua;mso-highlight:aqua&amp;#34; %)merely feed this corrupt (%%)form of the (% style=&amp;#34;background:aqua;mso-highlight: aqua&amp;#34; %)social(%%). (% style=&amp;#34;background:aqua;mso-highlight:aqua&amp;#34; %)What is the point (%%)of setting a purpose for an enlightened dimension of the political and the social spheres, (% style=&amp;#34;background:aqua;mso-highlight: aqua&amp;#34; %)when it&amp;#39;s becoming increasingly obvious, most particularly in the economic sphere, that these things are caught up with much stranger purposes, if not indeed with no purpose at all(%%)? There&amp;#39;s a kind of savage delusion and – not to put too fine a point on it – stupid­ity, in stubbornly pressing on in the right direction when there is no direction, in wishing to change the form of the equation when it&amp;#39;s equal to zero. 
__            (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:9.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Just look at all the battles everywhere on corrupt fronts: in the electoral system, where people are led to fight for equivalent castes; in the employment field, where everyone has to fight to find a place in a system of exploitation, a relatively favoured spot in a labour market which simultaneously serves the government as a black-mailing technique(%%). (% style=&amp;#34;background:aqua;mso-highlight: aqua&amp;#34; %)__Everywhere we&amp;#39;re trapped in false problems, false alternatives, false issues, in which we lose out come what may__(%%).\\

(% class=&amp;#34;tag&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;tag&amp;#34; %)
This conception of liberatory politics is rooted in the textual utopia of oppressive mobility which denies true liberation while perpetuating colonialism, patriarchy, and otherization.

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
**~ **

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;cite&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Pritchard 2000(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 7.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)(Elizabeth A. doctorate from Harvard University.  The Way Out West: Development and the Rhetoric of Mobility in Postmodern Feminist Theory.  Hypatia 15.3 (2000) 45-72.  Project Muse.)

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Michel Foucault&amp;#39;s analysis of Immanuel Kant&amp;#39;s essay &amp;#34;What is Enlightenment?&amp;#34; casts a brilliant light on the complexity and possible continuity of a strand of Enlightenment thought.(%%) __Foucault observes that Kant provides (% style=&amp;#34;background:aqua;mso-highlight:aqua&amp;#34; %)no substantive rendering of the Enlightenment(%%). Kant defines Enlightenment as &amp;#34;man&amp;#39;s emergence from his self-incurred immaturity or tutelage&amp;#34;__ (Kant 1970, 54). __Kant&amp;#39;s Enlightenment (% style=&amp;#34;background:aqua; mso-highlight:aqua&amp;#34; %)consists in (%%)**a movement away from a lesser state. He does not supply, however(% style=&amp;#34;background:aqua;mso-highlight:aqua&amp;#34; %), a fleshed-out description of (%%)what (% style=&amp;#34;background:aqua;mso-highlight:aqua&amp;#34; %)the better state (%%)is into which one is to enter**. Kant writes of human nature that our &amp;#34;original destiny lies precisely in such progress&amp;#34;__ (Kant 1970, 57; italics added). __A destiny of progress is no destiny. Destiny~-~-which suggests fate~-~-is derived from the__ End Page 48 __Latin destinare which mean &amp;#34;to fasten down or secure.&amp;#34; &amp;#123;&amp;#123;id name=&amp;#34;REF6&amp;#34;/}}6url:http://muse.jhu.edu.ezproxy.baylor.edu/journals/hypatia/v015/15.3pritchard.html#FOOT6 The point, for Kant, is **to become unfastened**. Kant&amp;#39;s Enlightenment is signified by open-endedness, metaphors of which are sprinkled throughout his writings__. For instance, he asserts, &amp;#34;Men will of their own accord gradually work their way out of barbarism so long as artificial measures are not deliberately adopted to keep them in it,&amp;#34; (Kant 1970, 59; italics added). __Foucault argues, therefore, that Kant sees Enlightenment as **an &amp;#34;exit,&amp;#34; a &amp;#34;way out**.&amp;#34; Foucault also asserts that this discourse of an exit or way out is part of what he describes as the Enlightenment &amp;#34;attitude&amp;#34; of **being &amp;#34;at the frontiers&amp;#34;~-~-of analyzing the limits imposed upon us and experimenting with going beyond them.** And it is this attitude, he offers, that may be &amp;#34;the thread that . . . connects us with the Enlightenment&amp;#34;__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)(Foucault 1984, 43, 42, 50).

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Foucault&amp;#39;s analysis of the Enlightenment correlates progress (read: development) with a spatial story of mobility. To become enlightened is to exit from a kind of bondage; it is to cross a frontier, a border. Kant does insist that what is necessary for Enlightenment is freedom.(%%) __Foucault notes that an alternate &amp;#34;rendering&amp;#34; of Kant&amp;#39;s Enlightenment would be the &amp;#34;undefined work of freedom&amp;#34;__ (Foucault 1984, 46; italics added). __Kant does provide some contours to his understanding of freedom. But I would argue that they only bolster Foucault&amp;#39;s reading of Kant&amp;#39;s emphasis upon &amp;#34;exiting.&amp;#34; Freedom is the &amp;#34;public use of one&amp;#39;s reason.&amp;#34; Kant compares the private and public distinction to the difference between being caught up in a machine and addressing the world in a cosmopolitan society, respectively. The private use of reason is restricted; one performs a role in private, that is, as officer, minister, taxpayer, etc. and must up-hold the contractual duties of this role. One can only speak and act from the authorized scripts that are apportioned to these roles. In the private use of reason one is &amp;#34;acting on a commission imposed from outside&amp;#34;__ (Kant 1970, 57). (% style=&amp;#34;background:aqua;mso-highlight:aqua&amp;#34; %)__Through __(%%)__the public use of (% style=&amp;#34;background:aqua;mso-highlight:aqua&amp;#34; %)reason, one steps out of a restrictive private role and addresses the &amp;#34;world at large,&amp;#34; that is, the reading public, linked across national frontiers. **In this textual utopia, the terms of relationships and institutions are continuously subject to debate and revision. In this open-ended global space there can be no restrictions or barriers to argument.** The private sphere is &amp;#34;domestic&amp;#34; and constraining; the public is &amp;#34;cosmopolitan&amp;#34; and dynamic(%%)__(% style=&amp;#34;background:aqua;mso-highlight:aqua&amp;#34; %) (%%)(Kant 1970, 57). &amp;#123;&amp;#123;id name=&amp;#34;REF7&amp;#34;/}}7url:http://muse.jhu.edu.ezproxy.baylor.edu/journals/hypatia/v015/15.3pritchard.html#FOOT7

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)
__To be free, to be modern, to develop is to get out of a situation of confinement. The modern West&amp;#39;s understanding of liberty relies upon a narrative of mobility, of openness and dynamism. Even before Kant, at the threshold of the period of the Enlightenment, Thomas Hobbes wrote, &amp;#34;Liberty, that we may define it, is nothing else but an absence of the lets and hindrances of motion. . . . Every man hath more or less liberty, as he hath more or less space in which he employs himself. . . . The more ways a man may move himself, the more liberty he hath&amp;#34;__ (Hobbes 1949, 109-10). &amp;#123;&amp;#123;id name=&amp;#34;REF8&amp;#34;/}}8url:http://muse.jhu.edu.ezproxy.baylor.edu/journals/hypatia/v015/15.3pritchard.html#FOOT8 This __reflexivity of freedom and __End Page 49 __mobility constitutes the central metaphor of modern liberalism&amp;#39;s doctrine of negative freedom. This is freedom as the &amp;#34;absence of constraints.&amp;#34; &amp;#123;&amp;#123;id name=&amp;#34;REF9&amp;#34;/}}9url:http://muse.jhu.edu.ezproxy.baylor.edu/journals/hypatia/v015/15.3pritchard.html#FOOT9 Negative freedom is freedom from hindrance or restriction. To be free is to be mobile; it is to be unencumbered by borders of place or location.__

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)
__This emphasis upon mobility as the measure of freedom, and thus of progress and development, is also reflected in Enlightenment economic theory__. (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height: 115%&amp;#34; %)The economists Adam Smith and David Ricardo advocated free trade as the engine of growth for the English economy; otherwise, they cautioned, the English economy would remain &amp;#34;closed&amp;#34; (Nehmet 1995, 40). According to Smith&amp;#39;s &amp;#34;vent-for-surplus&amp;#34; theory, &amp;#34;foreign&amp;#34; markets were to act as vents, allowing for the escape or exit of the surplus of European nations (Nehmet 1995, 40). (%%)__There can be no doubt that trade designed to open up and expand the markets of Europe was an engine of colonialism and its spin-off, &amp;#34;development.&amp;#34;__

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)
__This Enlightenment equation of mobility, modernity, and the West has had a profound influence on the construction of &amp;#34;development&amp;#34; as both a social science and foreign policy of the West__. (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)The U.S. policy of &amp;#34;development&amp;#34; was announced by President Harry S. Truman in 1949: &amp;#34;We must embark on a bold new program for making the benefits of our scientific advances and industrial progress available for the improvement and growth of underdeveloped areas. More than half of the people of the world are living in conditions approaching misery. . . . Their economic life is primitive and stagnant. . . . Our imponderable resources in the technical knowledge are constantly growing and are inexhaustible&amp;#34; (Truman 1950, 1366; Porter 1995, 66-67; italics added). Truman supplied no destination or fixed horizon of development as a goal to be reached. Rather, Truman&amp;#39;s rhetoric betrays a binary opposition that exalted the mobility of the modern West and deplored the stasis of the underdeveloped world.

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;background:aqua;mso-highlight:aqua&amp;#34; %)**__One of the earliest development economists wrote that the task of Western development was &amp;#34;To break through the barriers of stagnation in a backward country, to ignite the imaginations of men, and to place their energies in the service of economic development. . . . What is needed is to remove the mountains of routine and prejudice__**(%%)**__&amp;#34;__** (Gerschenkron 1992, 87; Cowen and Shenton 1995, 44). This same binary of stasis and mobility is evident in W. W. Rostow&amp;#39;s Stages of Economic Growth (Rostow 1990), the most influential blue-print of the early development programs__. His outline sketches a transition from the fatalistic production **&amp;#34;ceiling&amp;#34;** of traditionalism through the stages of &amp;#34;take-off,&amp;#34; the drive to maturity, and finally, the arrival at high mass consumption. Rowstow&amp;#39;s reference to &amp;#34;high mass consumption&amp;#34; suggests that a goal of development is material satiation. Nonetheless, even this &amp;#34;goal&amp;#34; belies the logic of development I have identified insofar as capitalist development is predicated upon schooling traditional societies, perhaps engaged in small-scale sustainable economies, in an everexpanding consumerism. Backward, End Page 50 stagnant societies are hemmed in, in part, due to the finitude of their desires; their wants and their concomitant production levels have a fatalistic &amp;#34;ceiling.&amp;#34; 10url:http://muse.jhu.edu.ezproxy.baylor.edu/journals/hypatia/v015/15.3pritchard.html#FOOT10__

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;background:aqua;mso-highlight:aqua&amp;#34; %)**__This development binary of mobility and stasis is, of course, also gendered__**(%%). Catherine Scott argues that &amp;#34;(% style=&amp;#34;background:aqua;mso-highlight: aqua&amp;#34; %)__Modernity has been envisioned, particularly by modernization theorists, in opposition to a feminized and traditional household__(%%)__&amp;#34;__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)(Scott 1995, 5). &amp;#123;&amp;#123;id name=&amp;#34;REF11&amp;#34;/}}11url:http://muse.jhu.edu.ezproxy.baylor.edu/journals/hypatia/v015/15.3pritchard.html#FOOT11 She elaborates this oppositional framework as follows: The dependent or underdeveloped entity is depicted as a soft and undifferentiated economy of affective kin relations enveloped within tradition (read: feminine); in contrast, the modern state is a market economy of impersonal relations entailing hard, articulated, and universal rules (read: masculine). The first is static, the second dynamic. The role of the latter is to assist in the severing of affective ties which keep underdeveloped entities (they can scarcely be called &amp;#34;states&amp;#34;) in a perpetual state of immaturity. Scott&amp;#39;s analysis employs aspects of feminist object-relations theory. Whatever one may think of these theories, a concrete indicator that a predominant strand of the Western tale of development is a story of mobility, more specifically of &amp;#34;exits&amp;#34; and &amp;#34;ways out&amp;#34; (of households), is that shelter only became a development issue in 1985 (Tinker 1993).

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)A careful reading of the rhetoric that informs the equation of development, modernity, and the West reveals that various spokespersons for development do not, contra Slater, supply a &amp;#34;final destination&amp;#34; for development. Rather,(%%) __it is the repudiation of location and its concomitant attributes of closure and stasis that characterize a particular Enlightenment discourse of &amp;#34;development.&amp;#34; This repudiation of location is characterized as a matter of breaking out of the confines of a feminized household and the cycles of a tradition-bound culture. Traditional society is homogeneous, feminine, and static, whereas modern society is highly differentiated and dynamic.__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Jonathan Crush&amp;#39;s observation captures the rhetorical gesture that I have insisted is an Enlightenment legacy: &amp;#34;Collectivities . . . were assigned a set of characteristics which suggested not only a low place in the hierarchy of achievement but a terminal condition of stasis, forever becalmed until the healing winds of modernity and development begin to blow. . . . Development animates the static&amp;#34; (Crush 1995, 9-10). &amp;#123;&amp;#123;id name=&amp;#34;REF12&amp;#34;/}}12url:http://muse.jhu.edu.ezproxy.baylor.edu/journals/hypatia/v015/15.3pritchard.html#FOOT12

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Other scholars of the modern West have remarked upon the significance of this binary of closure and openness as a shorthand for what it is that distinguishes the modern West from the times and places that are neither. Peter Gay insists that the Enlightenment entailed a profound shift from a near universal fear of change to a fear of stagnation (Gay 1966, 2:3). Similarly, Jonathan Z. Smith argues that it is a peculiar feature of the modern West that it identifies itself as the diasporic culture as opposed to the stasis of archaic cultures. Smith writes: &amp;#34;The West is active, it makes history, it is visible, it is human. The non-Western world is static, it undergoes history, it is invisible, it is non-human&amp;#34; End Page 51 (Smith 1993, 295). And Jean(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:aqua;mso-highlight:aqua&amp;#34; %)__Baudrillard recalls that during the Cold War, which is when the project of U.S. development of the Third World began, the &amp;#34;congealed&amp;#34; state was the recurrent metaphor of the &amp;#34;East,&amp;#34; and &amp;#34;fluidity&amp;#34; that of the &amp;#34;West__(%%)__&amp;#34; __(Baudrillard 1990, 100).

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)
__Despite the preponderance of this rhetoric of mobility in Enlightenment discourses, a number of postmodern feminists deploy this same rhetoric in their critiques of patriarchy, Enlightenment, and modernity.__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height: 115%&amp;#34; %)This is the case despite their various insights into the politics of location. Hélène Cixous, for instance, is wise to patriarchy&amp;#39;s tendency to feminize bounded space. She writes, &amp;#34;You women represent the eternal threat, the anticulture for us. We don&amp;#39;t stay in your houses; we are not going to remain in your beds. We wander. . . .&amp;#34; Cixous then turns around and borrows this sense of progressivity as consisting in a way out, only she is careful to reverse its gender. Speaking of the impossibility of &amp;#34;enclosing&amp;#34; a feminine practice of writing, Cixous writes, &amp;#34; the feminine practice of writing takes place and will take place somewhere other than in the territories subordinated to philosophical theoretical domination. It will not let itself think except through subjects that break automatic functions, border runners never subjugated by any authority&amp;#34; (Cixous 1986, 67, 92).

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Similarly, Luce Irigaray describes the claustrophobic space of phallogocentric discourse as follows: &amp;#34;From this encircling projective machinery, no reality escapes unscathed. . . . The whole is already circumscribed and determined by his discourse&amp;#34; (Irigaray 1985, 203-4). Hence, Irigaray is intent upon &amp;#34;. . . starting from an &amp;#39;outside&amp;#39; that is exempt, in part, from phallocratic law&amp;#34; (Irigaray 1985, 68). Irigiray is looking for a way out of the closure that is patriarchy. Kant was looking for an &amp;#34;exit&amp;#34;; Irigaray is looking for an &amp;#34;outside.&amp;#34; Correlative to the modern man whose development consists in his exiting the feminine household, Cixous admonishes women to become &amp;#34;border-runners,&amp;#34; and Irigaray advocates homelessness for women: &amp;#34;No longer spellbound by the fear of being without shelter. Unreservedly abandoning themselves to the unbounded open, holding nothing back&amp;#34; (Irigaray 1991, 216).

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)
__There is, then, a deep irony lurking in these critiques of patriarchy. Whereas the modern man of the Enlightenment attempts to escape the bounded and undifferentiated feminine household, Cixous and Irigaray wish to exit the enclosure of sameness that is patriarchy. This implies, of course, that these feminists are redeploying a patriarchal trope, that is, the repudiation, and perhaps violation, of the boundaries of location.__

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)This implicit equation between advancement/development and mobility continues in more recent postmodern feminist theory that addresses the fashioning of subjectivity. These feminists do not explicitly reject locatedness; rather they set out to problematize locatedness. These feminists acknowledge the fact that one cannot simply disown boundaries of association (a move which may be seen as attempting to evade all responsibility and guilt). Nonetheless, I do wish to encourage these postmodern feminists to scrutinize more End Page 52 carefully their rhetoric. Whereas they problematize closure, fixity, boundaries, and settlement in the making of subjects, they do not sufficiently problematize metaphors of mobility. Hence, they do not own up to the (potentially troubling) echoes of Enlightenment which sound in their work.

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)For instance, Kathy Ferguson advocates &amp;#34;mobile subjectivities&amp;#34; that &amp;#34;trouble fixed boundaries&amp;#34; of identity. &amp;#123;&amp;#123;id name=&amp;#34;REF13&amp;#34;/}}13url:http://muse.jhu.edu.ezproxy.baylor.edu/journals/hypatia/v015/15.3pritchard.html#FOOT13 Ferguson argues that her advocacy of mobile subjectivities resists a globalizing move which seeks a unity based on sameness. I see, however, traces of a globalizing move in her account. Ferguson states that &amp;#34;Mobile subjectivities appear not just in discourse but in institutions as well; they are material as well as semiotic actors&amp;#34; (Ferguson 1993, 162). But do all subjectivities have equal amounts of mobility in institutions? Ferguson describes mobile subjectivities as &amp;#34;moving across and along axes of power&amp;#34; (154). I would counter that(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:aqua;mso-highlight:aqua&amp;#34; %)__the discourse of mobility is itself an axis of power. Connected to this point__(%%), Ferguson observes that mobile (% style=&amp;#34;background:aqua;mso-highlight:aqua&amp;#34; %)__subjectivities are &amp;#34;testy and argumentative (but need not be imperialistic)&amp;#34; (163). She might have explored why the connection between mobility and imperialism occured to her__(%%)__.__

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) 

