(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Baudrillard 2001

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)To be able to disobey moral rules and laws(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %), to be able to disobey others, is a mark of freedom.  But the ability to disobey oneself marks the highest stage of freedom.  Obeying one’s own will is an even worse vice than being enslaved to one’s passions.  It is certainly worse than enslavement to the will of others.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)  And (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)it is,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)indeed, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)those who submit themselves mercilessly to their own decisions who fill the greater part of the authoritarian ranks, alleging sacrifice on their own part to impose even greater sacrifices on others. Each stage of servitude is both more subtle an

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Robinson 2012 (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)/Andrew, Political Theorist, Activist Based in the UK and research fellow affiliated to the Centre for the Study of Social and Global Justice (CSSGJ), University of Nottingham, “Jean Baudrillard: The Rise of Capitalism and the Exclusion of Death”, March 30,  http:~/~/ceasefiremagazine.co.uk/in-theory-baudrillard-2/

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in;text-align:justify;text-justify: inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Symbolic exchange (%%)– or rather, its (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)suppression – plays a central role in the emergence of capitalism(%%). (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Baudrillard sees a change happening over time(%%). (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)Regimes based on symbolic exchange(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)(differences are exchangeable and related)(%%) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)are replaced by regimes based on equivalence(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)(everything is, or means, the same).(%%) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Ceremony gives way to spectacle(%%), (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height: 115%&amp;#34; %)immanence to transcendence.¶ Baudrillard’s view of capitalism is derived from Marx’s analysis of value. Baudrillard accepts Marx’s view that capitalism is based on a general equivalent. Money is the general equivalent because it can be exchanged for any commodity. In turn, it expresses the value of abstract labour-time. Abstract labour-time is itself an effect of the regimenting of processes of life, so that different kinds of labour can be compared(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; line-height: 115%; mso-ansi-font-size: 8pt; line-height: 115%&amp;#34; %). (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Capitalism is derived from the autonomisation or separation of economics from the rest of life. It turns economics into the ‘reality-principle’. It is a kind of sorcery, connected in some way to the disavowed symbolic level. It subtly shifts the social world from an exchange of death with the Other to an eternal return of the Same. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)Capitalism functions by reducing everything(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) to a regime(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %) based on (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)value and the (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)production of value.(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)To be accepted (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)by capital, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)something must contribute value.(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height: 115%&amp;#34; %)This creates an immense regime of social exchange. However, this social exchange has little in common with symbolic exchange. It ultimately depends on the mark of value itself being unexchangeable. Capital must be endlessly accumulated. States must not collapse. Capitalism thus introduces the irreversible into social life, by means of accumulation.¶ According to Baudrillard,(%%) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)capitalism rests on an obsession with the abolition of death. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Capitalism tries to abolish death through accumulation(%%). It tries to ward off ambivalence (associated with death) through value (associated with life). (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)But this is bound to fail.(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)General equivalence (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)– the basis of capitalism – (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)is (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)itself (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)the ever-presence of death(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %). (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)The more the system runs from death, the more it places everyone in solitude, facing their own death.(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) Life itself is fundamentally ambivalent. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)The attempt to abolish death through fixed value is itself deathly(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height:115%;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)¶ Accumulation also spreads to other fields. The idea of progress, and linear time, comes from the accumulation of time, and of stockpiles of the past. The idea of truth comes from the accumulation of scientific knowledge.(%%) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Biology rests on the separation of living and non-living(%%). (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height: 115%&amp;#34; %)According to Baudrillard, such accumulations are now in crisis. For instance, the accumulation of the past is undermined, because historical objects now have to be concealed to be preserved – otherwise they will be destroyed by excessive consumption. Value is produced from the residue or remainder of an incomplete symbolic exchange. The repressed, market value, and sign-value all come from this remainder. To destroy the remainder would be to destroy value.¶ Capitalist exchange is always based on negotiation, even when it is violent. The symbolic order does not know this kind of equivalential exchange or calculation.(%%) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)And capitalist extraction is always one-way. It amounts to a non-reversible aggression in which one act (of dominating or killing) cannot be returned by the other. It is also this regime which produces scarcity(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height: 115%&amp;#34; %)– Baudrillard here endorses Sahlins’ argument. Capitalism produces the Freudian “death drive”, which is actually an effect of the capitalist culture of death. For Baudrillard, the limit to both Marx and Freud is that they fail to theorise the separation of the domains they study – the economy and the unconscious. It is the separation which grounds their functioning, which therefore only occurs under the regime of the code.¶ Baudrillard also criticises theories of desire, including those of Deleuze, Foucault, Freud and Lacan. He believes (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)desire comes into existence based on repression. It is an effect of the denial of the symbolic.(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Liberated energies always leave a new remainder; they do not escape the basis of the unconscious in the remainder. Baudrillard argues that indigenous groups do not claim to live naturally or by their desires – they simply claim to live in societies. This social life is an effect of the symbolic. Baudrillard therefore criticises the view that human liberation can come about through the liberation of desire. He thinks that such a liberation will keep certain elements of the repression of desire active.¶ Baudrillard argues that the processes which operate collectively in indigenous groups are repressed into the unconscious in metropolitan societies. This leads to the autonomy of the psyche as a separate sphere. It is only after this repression has occurred that a politics of desire becomes conceivable. He professes broad agreement with the Deleuzian project of unbinding energies from fixed categories and encouraging flows and intensities. However, he is concerned that capitalism can recuperate such releases of energy, disconnecting them so they can eventually reconnect to it. Unbinding and drifting are not fatal to capitalism, because capitalism itself unbinds things, and re-binds things which are unbound. What is fatal to it is, rather, reversibility.¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)Capitalism continues to be haunted by the forces it has repressed(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %).(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Separation does not destroy the remainder. Quite the opposite. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)The remainder continues to exist, and gains power from its repression. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)This (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)turns the double or shadow into something unquiet, vampiric, and threatening. It(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %) becomes an image of the forgotten dead(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %).(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Anything which reminds us of the repressed aspects excluded from the subject is experienced as uncanny and threatening. It becomes the ‘obscene’, which is present in excess over the ‘scene’ of what is imagined.¶ This is different from theories of lack, such as the Lacanian Real. Baudrillard’s remainder is an excess rather than a lack. It is the carrier of the force of symbolic exchange.¶ Modern culture dreams of radical difference. The reason for this is that it exterminated radical difference by simulating it. The energy of production, the unconscious, and signification all in fact come from the repressed (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; line-height: 115%; mso-ansi-font-size: 8pt; line-height: 115%&amp;#34; %)remainder(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %). Our culture is dead from having broken the pact with monstrosity, with radical difference. The West continues to perpetrate genocide on indigenous groups(%%). (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)But for Baudrillard(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8pt; line-height: 115%; mso-ansi-font-size: 8pt; line-height: 115%&amp;#34; %),(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) it did the same thing to itself first – destroying its own indigenous logics of symbolic exchange(%%). (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Indigenous groups have also increasingly lost the symbolic dimension, as modern forms of life have been imported or imposed. This according to Baudrillard produces chronic confusion and instability.¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Gift-exchange is radically subversive of the system(%%). (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)This is(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)not because it is rebellious. Baudrillard thinks the system can survive defections or exodus. It is(%%) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)because it counterposes a different ‘principle of sociality’ to that of the dominant system(%%). (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)According to Baudrillard,(%%) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)the mediations of capitalism exist so that nobody has the opportunity to offer a symbolic challenge or an irreversible gift. They exist to keep the symbolic at(%%) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)bay. The affective charge of death remains present among the oppressed(%%), (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)but not with the ‘properly symbolic rhythm’ of immediate retaliation.¶ The Church and State also exist based on the elimination of symbolic exchange. Baudrillard is highly critical of Christianity for what he takes to be a cult of suffering, solitude and death. He sees the Church as central to the destruction of earlier forms of community based on symbolic exchange.¶ Baudrillard seems to think that earlier forms of the state and capitalism retained some degree of symbolic exchange, but in an alienated, partially repressed form. For instance, the imaginary of the ‘social contract’ was based on the idea of a sacrifice – this time of liberty for the common good. In psychoanalysis, symbolic exchange is displaced onto the relationship to the master-signifier. I haven’t seen Baudrillard say it directly, but the impression he gives is that this is a distorted, authoritarian imitation of the original symbolic exchange. Nonetheless, it retains some of its intensity and energy. Art, theatre and language have worked to maintain a minimum of ceremonial power.¶ It is the reason older orders did not suffer the particular malaise of the present. It is easy to read certain passages in Baudrillard as if he is bemoaning the loss of these kinds of strong significations. This is initially how I read Baudrillard’s work. But on closer inspection, this seems to be a misreading. Baudrillard is nostalgic for repression only to the extent that the repressed continued to carry symbolic force as a referential. He is nostalgic for the return of symbolic exchange, as an aspect of diffuse, autonomous, dis-alienated social groups.¶ Death¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Death plays a central role(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height: 115%&amp;#34; %)in Baudrillard’s theory, and is closely related to symbolic exchange. According to Baudrillard, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)what we have lost above all in the transition to alienated society is the ability to engage in exchanges with death. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)Death should not be seen (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)here (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)in (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)purely (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)literal terms(%%). (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Baudrillard specifies early on that(%%) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)he does not mean an event affecting a body, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)but (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)rather, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)a form which destroys the determinacy of the subject and of value(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) (%%)– (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)which returns things to a state of indeterminacy(%%). (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Baudrillard certainly discusses actual deaths, risk-taking, suicide and so on. But he also sees death figuratively, in relation to the decomposition of existing relations, the “death” of the self-image or ego, the interchangeability of processes of life across different categories. For instance, eroticism or sexuality is related to death, because it leads to fusion and communication between bodies. Sexual reproduction carries shades of death because one generation replaces another. Baudrillard’s concept of death is thus quite similar to Bakhtin’s concept of the grotesque(%%). (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)Death refers to metamorphosis, reversibility, unexpected mutations, social change, subjective transformation, as well as physical death(%%).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)¶ (%%)According to Baudrillard,(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)indigenous groups see death as social, not natural or biological(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %). They see it as an effect of an adversarial will, which they must absorb. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)And they mark it with feasting and rituals. This is a way of preventing death from becoming an event which does not signify(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %).(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Such a non-signifying event is absolute disorder from the standpoint of symbolic exchange. For Baudrillard, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)the west’s idea of a biological, material death is actually an idealist illusion, ignoring the sociality of death(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) (%%)Poststructuralists generally maintain that (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11.0pt;line-height:115%;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)the problems of the present are rooted in the splitting of life into binary oppositions(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %).(%%) For Baudrillard, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)the division between life and death is the original, founding opposition on which the others are founded(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %). (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)After this first split, a whole series of others have been created, confining particular groups – the “mad”, prisoners, children, the old, sexual minorities, women and so on(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) – to particular segregated situations(%%). (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)The definition of the ‘normal human’ has been narrowed over time. Today, nearly everyone belongs to one or another marked or deviant category.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)¶ (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)The original exclusion was of the dead – (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)it is defined as abnormal to be dead. “You livies hate us deadies”(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %).(%%) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)This first split and exclusion forms the basis, or archetype, for all the other splits and exclusions – along lines of gender, disability, species, class, and so on.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)This discrimination against the dead brings into being the modern experience of death. (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Baudrillard suggests that(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)**__death __**(%%)**__as we know it (% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)does not exist outside of this separation between living and dead.(%%)__**(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)The modern view of death is constructed on the model of the machine and the function. A machine either functions or it does not. The human body is treated as a machine(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)which similarly, either functions or does not. For Baudrillard, this misunderstands the nature of life and death.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)¶ (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)The modern view of death is also necessitated by the rise of subjectivity(%%). (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)The subject needs a beginning and an end, so as to be reducible to the story it tells(%%). (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)This requires an idea of death as an end. It is counterposed to the immortality of social institutions.(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height: 115%&amp;#34; %)In relation to individuals, ideas of religious immortality is simply an ideological cover for the real exclusion of the dead. But institutions try to remain truly immortal.(%%) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)Modern systems(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %), especially bureaucracies, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)no longer know (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)how to die – or (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)how to do anything but keep reproducing themselves.(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) The internalisation of the idea of the subject or the soul alienates us from our bodies,(%%) voices and so on. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)It creates a split(%%), as Stirner would say, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)between the category of ‘man’ and the ‘un-man’, the real self irreducible to such categories. It also individualises people, by destroying their actual connections to others(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %).

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNoSpacing&amp;#34; %)
**~ **

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Baudrillard explains in 89

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNoSpacing&amp;#34; %)
**//__ __//**

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNoSpacing&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:1.0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__The obsessive desire for survival__(%%) (and not for life) (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__is__(%%) a symptom of this state of affairs and doubtless also __the (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)most worrying(%%) sign of the degradation of the species.__ __If you think about (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)the forms that desire(%%) currently (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)takes(%%) –antinuclear shelters, cryogenization__, high-pressure therapy - __you see that they (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)are exactly the forms of extermination. To avoid dying, one chooses to withdraw into some protective bubble(%%) or other__. In this light, we should take it as a reassuring sign that people lost interest in antinuclear protection so quickly (the shelter market has become a mere prestige market, like the market for artworks or luxury yachts). It seems that people have become tired of nuclear blackmail and decided not to give in to it, leaving the threat of destruction hanging in mid-air over them, perhaps with an obscure sense of how unreal it is. A fine example of a vital reaction disguised as resignation. __‘(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)If we have to die, better to die in the open air than in an underground sarcophagus(%%).’ At a stroke an end is put to survival blackmail and life can go on.__

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNoSpacing&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:1.0in&amp;#34; %)
Everyone is weary of these apocalyptic visions - the great scenario of the nuclear threat, the theatrical negotiations, ‘Star Wars’. In the end, they defend themselves with a lack of imagination. Even attempts to stimulate that imagination in films like //The Last Day //have not worked. (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)__Nothing has ever been able to make this__(%%)__ nuclear scene - or obscenity - (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)credible(%%). With delicate matters like this (as with cancer), imagining death has the effect of bringing the fatal event closer.__ The masses’ silent indifference to nuclear pathos (whether it comes from the nuclear powers or from antinuclear campaigners) is therefore a great sign of hope and a political fact of the utmost importance.

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNoSpacing&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNoSpacing&amp;#34; %)
This is Baudrillard in 05:

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%;mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)__Freedom?__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)  A dream!

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%;mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)            __Everyone aspires to it, or at least gives the impression of aspiring fervently to it.__

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%;mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)            If it is an illusion, it has become a vital illusion.

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%;mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)            __In morality__, mores and mentalities, __this movement__, which seems to well up from the depths of history, __is towards irrevocable emancipation.__

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%;mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)            And if some aspects may seem excessive or contradictory, we still experience the dizzying thrill of this emancipation.

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%;mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)            Better: __the whole of our system turns this liberation into a duty, a moral obligation – to the point where it is difficult to distinguish this liberation compulsion from a ‘natural’ aspiration towards, a ‘natural’ demand for, freedom.__

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%;mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %) 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%;mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)Now, it is clear that, __where all forms of servitude are concerned, everyone wants to through them off; where all forms of constraint are concerned – physical constrains or constraints of law – everyone wishes to be free of them.  This is such a vital reaction that there is barely, in the end, any need of an idea of freedom to express it.__

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%;mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;&amp;#34; %)            __Things become problematic when the prospect arises for the subject of being answerable solely for him/herself in an undifferentiated universe.  For this symbolic disobligation is accompanied by a general deregulation.  And it is in this universe __of free electrons –__ free to become anything whatever in a system of generalized exchange – __that __we see growing. Simultaneously, a contradictory impulse, a resistance to this availability of everyone and everything that is every bit as deep as the desire for freedom.  A passion for rules of whatever kind that is equal to the passion for deregulation.__

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

=== The politics they call for will inevitably be co-opted and can never achieve effective change.  Their link misunderstands our strategy of indifference as a passive form of nihilism without care – yet, our strategy is one of positive indifference which allows for true caring, resistance and political change ===

===  ===

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)** **

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Bogard 1990(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)** **(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 7.0pt;line-height:115%;mso-bidi-font-weight:bold&amp;#34; %)(William, professor at Whitman College.  Closing down the social: Baudrillard’s Challenge to Contemporary Sociology.  //Sociological Theory//, Vol. 8, No. 1. (Spring, 1990), pp. 1-15.)

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)For sociologists who have accepted the humanist premises of their discipline, such a project will appear as the height of irrationality and irresponsibility, and we can imagine their incredulity: Can Baudrillard really be serious about this? Is it rational to think that mass indifference, if this indeed truly characterizes the climate of modern culture, is a form of resistance which itself must be met with indifference? And if so, to what conceivable end?(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) How can one remain indifferent to a world full of poverty, racism, and other forms of social injustice? Wouldn&amp;#39;t this only make matters worse, or at best allow these problems to continue to fester? (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Doesn&amp;#39;t Baudrillard, rather than creating theoretical possibilities for &amp;#34;conquering&amp;#34; a world which has become indifferent, in truth only succeed in making both himself and theory indifferent to, and thus at the mercy of, all possibilities? (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Baudrillard himself does not address, let alone ask, these kinds of questions, and rightly so, because they identify indifference with passive nihilism or a lack of caring, neither of which is intended in Baudrillard&amp;#39;s meaning of the term. Baudrillard&amp;#39;s indifference(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %), I shall suggest,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;mso-bidi-font-weight: bold&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)is of an altogether different type, and I can think of no better way of describing it other than as a positive indifference, a kind of stoic posture that invites attack by &amp;#34;playing dead.&amp;#34; What he proposes is not passivity, but an active strategy designed to lure its opponent into making a self-defeating move, in effect turning the opponent&amp;#39;s own force into a weapon against it. (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Contrary to what a literal reading of Baudrillard might infer, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)indifference does not signify an uncaring attitude, nor is it inauthentic (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)(that is, Baudrillard is not just espousing a position he in fact does not hold). (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Rather, his indifference is an ironic-and, one might add, tragic-response to a world which he believes has closed off virtually all other forms of resistance. For Baudrillard, care, however highly we value this virtue, is sacrificed in order to oppose an enemy for whom care no longer has any meaning. At best, one can only challenge the present order-the simulated order-with a simulated indifference. Only such a strategy manages to avoid, for the time being at least, the overwhelming capacity of this order to coopt the power of resistance for its own ends.

=== Our strategy is one of maximum political energy – it does not deny politics, but rather interviews in the most effective manner ===

===  ===

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
**~ **

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;cite&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Chaloupka 1990(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;line-height:115%;mso-bidi-font-weight: bold&amp;#34; %)(William, Immodest Modesty: Antinuclear Discourse, Lifestyle Politics, and Intervention Strategies.  //International Studies Quarterly//, Vol. 34, No. 3, Special Issue: Speaking the Language of Exile: Dissidence in International Studies. (Sep., 1990), pp. 341-351.)

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:9.0pt; line-height:115%;mso-bidi-font-weight:bold&amp;#34; %) 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:9.0pt; line-height:115%;mso-bidi-font-weight:bold&amp;#34; %) Baudrillard&amp;#39;s idea of the social-some common ground of thought, action, coercion, and negotiation-is distinct from that presumed by any citizen attitude study. On one hand(%%), __the social is deconstructed when displaced by &amp;#34;the masses,&amp;#34; a floating referent which could point to philosophical or physical substance, to a group, or even-in French-to geophysical or electrical properties.j But on the other hand, the mass can be subjected to commentary__, an opportunity opened, for example, by Nixonian references to a &amp;#34;silent majority.&amp;#34; In either case, __&amp;#34;the mass is what remains when the social has been completely removed&amp;#34;__ (Baudrillard, 1983:6-7). **__Opportunity for action may remain__**__, but it would not be informed by a society which understands itself to be a society, capable of concerted action.__

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)
If the social has been removed-or if it never existed-what we have called &amp;#34;sociality&amp;#34; may actually be its simulation. **__Without a social model, we could no longer take for granted our assumption that the actions of a group or individual &amp;#34;reflect&amp;#34; or &amp;#34;represent&amp;#34; a position__**__. In the realm of simulation-in the simulacrum-the terms usually attached to a politics of significance or signification can be reversed. Even more dramatically, these terms can **disappear**. In an important example of both of these effects, the apathy of the contemporary mass is, in Baudrillard&amp;#39;s telling, an absorbing, unreflective &amp;#34;black hole.&amp;#34; But that indifference is also a positive development, a sort of strategic refusal, the masses&amp;#39; &amp;#34;true, their only practice&amp;#34;__ (Baudrillard, 1983:14). __If the masses have escaped signification and its political form, representation, this does not necessarily mean that they have &amp;#34;failed.&amp;#34;__

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)
__&amp;#34;As Nietzsche well knew, it is in this disregard for a social, psychological, historical truth, in this exercise of simulacra as such, that **the maximum of political energy is found**, where the political is a game and is not yet given a reason&amp;#34;__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height:115%;mso-bidi-font-weight:bold&amp;#34; %)(Baudrillard, 1983:16).(%%) __Seen this way, **the indifference of the masses escapes a politics which has been &amp;#34;dominated by representative mechanisms&amp;#34; for three centuries**__ (% style=&amp;#34;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;line-height:115%;mso-bidi-font-weight:bold&amp;#34; %)(Baudrillard, 1983:17). Marx suggested that the masses would represent social fact to political institutions, eventually dissolving the political, withering it away. In this sense, it may not be so strange to imagine that the social is what disappeared instead (Baudrillard, 1983:18). And without a signifiable &amp;#34;social,&amp;#34; any politics based on representation begins to falter.

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;mso-bidi-font-size: 10.0pt;line-height:115%;mso-bidi-font-weight:bold&amp;#34; %)Marx also argued that the negation of the social-alienation-confirmed the social possibility, but Baudrillard (1981 :147-48) closes that escape route.(%%) __The silent majorities still speak, but they refuse to be represented__. (% style=&amp;#34;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt; line-height:115%;mso-bidi-font-weight:bold&amp;#34; %)&amp;#34;And in this sense, far from being a form of alienation, this silence is an absolute weapon. . . Tlhis is its mode of defense, its particular mode of retaliation&amp;#34; (1983:22-23). Still, Baudrillard is continually evasive on diagnosis. These strategies are dangerous, they require energy to maintain, but they also present opportunities for intervention. The masses join the media and terrorism in a &amp;#34;triangular affinity&amp;#34; (1983:58), but that affinity may only help us account for developments which otherwise seem merely brutal. (%%)**__This demise of representation, its removal from the center of all political acts, __**is an important development, but it **__does not necessarily end politics__**__. **An expressive practice could deny representation and intervene in politics instead through disruption and ironic juxtaposition**__. (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:9.0pt;line-height:115%; mso-bidi-font-weight:bold&amp;#34; %)In our present case, we might begin to wonder whether lifestyle expressions //represent //a preferred future, as they sometimes claim. Perhaps, instead, the whole system of solemn expression of political positions is somehow undermined by these solemn substitute lifestyles.

(% class=&amp;#34;BlockTitle&amp;#34; %)
 

=== Instead of making politics impossible, our position of artifice and recognition of the state of the social and of language allows us to achieve true political change and formulate the most effective strategies of resistance– the politics called for by the affirmative undermine all political speech ===

===  ===

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
**~ **

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;cite&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Chaloupka 1990 ((% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 7.0pt;line-height:115%;mso-bidi-font-weight:bold&amp;#34; %)William, Immodest Modesty: Antinuclear Discourse, Lifestyle Politics, and Intervention Strategies.  //International Studies Quarterly//, Vol. 34, No. 3, Special Issue: Speaking the Language of Exile: Dissidence in International Studies. (Sep., 1990), pp. 341-351.)

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
__ __

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)
__Rather than solidifying our relations with events and their sequences, language introduces oscillation, dissembly, memory, and waiting. The attempt to solidify foreign policy positions thus runs counter to what occurs within those positions at their most fundamental level. But **instead of making politics impossible, our recognition of language&amp;#39;s shifting, contradictory role enables responses**, **even if those responses will differ from those enabled by the enlightenment**.__ At this point &amp;#34;the self&amp;#34; becomes important to the post-structuralist position as well as to my present misreading of the lifestyle position. __The oscillation and contradiction rearrange the role of the speaker, that most central role in any politics which could emerge from the enlightenment. Even &amp;#34;the simple assertion &amp;#39;I speak,&amp;#34;&amp;#39; contains the speaker&amp;#39;s (and the statement&amp;#39;s) &amp;#34;threatening promise of its own disappearance, its future appearance&amp;#34; __(Foucault, 1987:58). __As the authorial self loses its status, an oscillation begins in politics as well as language. **Political speech is undermined**; the exterior, moral, critical distance promised by Habermas cannot hold. Neither can our commitment to reenact the world we prefer through alterations of grammar and syntax. But the same undermining has happened to structures and authorities who have imposed political forms. Those structures cannot be justified by the web of relationship to (the words) nature and necessity. The &amp;#34;future appearance&amp;#34; is uncertain, to be sure, but it also **threatens all political forms justified in this manner**. __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:9.0pt;line-height:115%;mso-bidi-font-weight:bold&amp;#34; %)They are exposed by the lifestyle critique.

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

(% align=&amp;#34;left&amp;#34; class=&amp;#34;BlockTitle&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:left&amp;#34; %)
 

(% align=&amp;#34;left&amp;#34; class=&amp;#34;BlockTitle&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:left&amp;#34; %)
 

=== And their interpretation causes the very political paralysis they fight against. ===

===  ===

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Antonio 95(%%) (Robert, Nietzsche’s Antisociology, American Journal of Sociology, Vol. 101, No. 1 (Jul., 1995), pp. 1-43 ~\~\stroud)

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left:.5in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)The &amp;#34;problem of the actor,&amp;#34; Nietzsche said, &amp;#34;troubled me for the longest time.&amp;#34;&amp;#39;12 He considered &amp;#34;roles&amp;#34; as &amp;#34;external,&amp;#34; &amp;#34;surface,&amp;#34; or &amp;#34;foreground&amp;#34; phenomena and viewed close personal identification with them as symptomatic of estrangement. While modern theorists saw differentiated roles and professions as a matrix of autonomy and reflexivity, Nietzsche held that persons (especially male professionals) in specialized occupations overidentify with their positions and engage in gross fabrications to obtain advancement. They look hesitantly to the opinion of others, asking themselves, &amp;#34;How ought I feel about this?&amp;#34; They are so thoroughly absorbed in simulating effective (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)role players(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) that they (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)have trouble being anything but actors(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)-&amp;#34;(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)The role has actually become the character(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %).&amp;#34; (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)This highly subjectified social self or simulator suffers devastating inauthenticity(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %). (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)The powerful authority(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) given the social (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)greatly amplifies(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Socratic culture&amp;#39;s already self-indulgent &amp;#34;inwardness(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %).&amp;#34; (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Integrity, decisiveness, spontaneity, and pleasure are undone by paralyzing overconcern about possible causes, meanings, and consequences of acts and unending internal dialogue about what others might think, expect, say, or do(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) (Nietzsche 1983, pp. 83-86; 1986, pp. 39-40; 1974, pp. 302-4, 316-17). Nervous rotation of socially appropriate (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)&amp;#34;masks&amp;#34; reduce(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)s (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)persons to hypostatized(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) &amp;#34;shadows,&amp;#34; &amp;#34;abstracts,&amp;#34; or (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)simulacra(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %). (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)One adopts &amp;#34;many roles(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %),&amp;#34; (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)playing them &amp;#34;badly and superficially&amp;#34; in the fashion of a stiff &amp;#34;puppet(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)play(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %).&amp;#34; Nietzsche asked, &amp;#34;Are you genuine? Or only an actor? A representative or that which is represented? . . . Or no more than an imitation of an actor?&amp;#34; Simulation is so pervasive that (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)it is hard to tell the copy from the genuine(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)article(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %); social selves &amp;#34;prefer the copies to the originals&amp;#34; (Nietzsche 1983, pp. 84-86; 1986, p. 136; 1974, pp. 232- 33, 259; 1969b, pp. 268, 300, 302; 1968a, pp. 26-27). Their inwardness and aleatory scripts foreclose genuine attachment to others. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)This type of actor cannot plan for the long term or participate in(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) enduring net- works of interdependence; such a person is neither willing nor able to be a &amp;#34;stone&amp;#34; in (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)the societal &amp;#34;edifice(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)&amp;#34; (Nietzsche 1974, pp. 302-4; 1986a, pp. 93-94). Superficiality rules in the arid subjectivized landscape. Neitzsche (1974, p. 259) stated, &amp;#34;One thinks with a watch in one&amp;#39;s hand, even as one eats one&amp;#39;s midday meal while reading the latest news of the stock market; (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)one lives as if one always &amp;#39;might miss out on something(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %). &amp;#39;&amp;#39;Rather do anything than nothing&amp;#39;: this principle, too, is merely a string to throttle all culture. . . . (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Living in a constant chase after gain compels people to expend their spirit to the point of exhaustion in continual(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) pretense and (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)overreaching(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) and anticipating others.&amp;#34;

(% class=&amp;#34;tag&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;tag&amp;#34; %)
 

=== No risk of the implication: our policy discourse is unable to spill over to construct broader social meanings or further political programs. ===

===  ===

(% class=&amp;#34;tag&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;cite&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Chandler 2007(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)(Dr. David, Professor of International Relations, Centre for the Study of Democracy, University of Westminster.  ‘Baudrillard and IR’ Panel: The EU’s Promotion of Democracy in the Balkans: The Power of Simulation and the Simulation of Power.  Draft paper prepared for the British International Studies Association Annual Conference 2007 Cambridge 17-19 December.)

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;card&amp;#34; %)
This paper follows (% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; %)Baudrillard’s view that (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)the ‘dissolution of the political subject’, i.e. the end of political projects of Left and Right, has created a crisis of representation and that the location of power is no longer clear(%%), that in fact,(% class=&amp;#34;underline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)political elites can no longer generate and externally project power, only simulate it.1(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)In the absence of any connection with the masses, with their own society, elites are unable to give policy-making a broader social meaning(%%), (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)enabling them to engage and mobilize social support for a political programme(%%).2 (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Baudrillard’s framework enables(%%) the articulation of a (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)critique of traditional Realist or Critical understandings of democracy export as dissimulation(%%), feigning ‘not to have what one has’, i.e., as a pretence that policy is not driven by self-interest or the needs of capital accumulation, through an understanding of policy practice in terms of simulation, which ‘is to feign to have what one hasn’t’: i.e., (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)the pretence that there are clear instrumental interests and ideological values being asserted(%%) by the EU.^^4^^

(% align=&amp;#34;left&amp;#34; class=&amp;#34;BlockTitle&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:left&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

(% style=&amp;#34;mso-element:para-border-div;border:solid windowtext 3.0pt; padding:1.0pt 4.0pt 1.0pt 4.0pt&amp;#34; %)
(((
= 1NR Evidence =
)))

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Coulter 12

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)…we live in a world where there is an increasing amount of information but less meaning(%%) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)while finding modernity collapsing under the weight of information with catastrophic implications for meaning: &amp;#34;where we think that information produces meaning, (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)//the opposite occurs//(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)&amp;#34;(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %).  (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)Meaning, truth, and the real are here (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)//reversed//(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)(divested of universal meaning) and restricted to local, partial objects(%%) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)This world, which we inhabit like living phantoms in the desert(%%) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)is a place where (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)//we may not have a politics//(% style=&amp;#34;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %), (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11.0pt;line-height:115%;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)//but we do have a strategy//(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %): (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)One must (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)//push //(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)at the(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)// insane consumption of energy in order to exterminate its concept//(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %).(%%) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)One must push at maximal repression in order to exterminate its concept. ...(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)//&amp;#39;One must push what is collapsing&amp;#39;//(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %), said Nietzsche ... .I am a terrorist and a nihilist in theory as the others are in weapons. Theoretical violence, not truth, is the only resource we have left us.”

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) 

(% style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)
=== (% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)The alternative is acceleration. The counterplan is this farcical acceleration, we replace the speculation that holds into place money with an infinite string of speculations that have no endpoint, in order to collapse the economic system. If they try and make a permutation, it wouldn&amp;#39;t make any sense, because we say financial collapse good, and they rely on the market to get to the impact of their aff. 100% of the argument is competitive.(%%) ===

===  ===

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) 

=== (% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:22.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)Systems of speculation are the same ones that create the systems of collapse; the financial crisis came about in 2008 because of the market place speculation that exceeded its material counterpart, and collapsed.(%%) ===

===  ===

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:22.0pt;line-height:115%;mso-bidi-font-weight:bold&amp;#34; %) 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleStyleBold12pt&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:13.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)McCallam 2012(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)(David, Department of French, SLC, University of Sheffield.  “The terrorist Earth? Some thoughts on Sade and Baudrillard.”  French Cultural Studies 23(3) 215–224)

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)This brings us to the final point of (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)convergence between (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)terrorism and natural disaster(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %): their(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)//overlapping discursive orders//(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) (%%)– (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)//future-oriented and prophetic//(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)These (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)are less the discourses of earthquake and terrorist themselves, but of their (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)//adversaries//(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %), the seismologist and the counter-terrorism expert, extreme examples of a globalised culture(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)//of prediction and pre-emption//(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %), (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)of weather forecasts, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)election (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)polls, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)economic (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)prognoses, (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)//climate-change models//(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %), etc(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;background: lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %). I(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)n fact, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)the terrorist works best when she acts most like the earthquake and says nothing, proclaims nothing in advance of the attack(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %). (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)//Their terrible latency is their strength//(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) − that of (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)the(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) sleeper cell and (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; background: lime; mso-highlight: lime&amp;#34; %)dormant volcano: a latency that (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)//often leads forecasters to doubt the possibility of their ever happening//(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%; background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %). Hence what natural disaster and terrorist act share is a paradoxical entry into reality, the almost unimaginable nature of their ‘becoming possible’(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) (Dupuy, 2008: 486). The Lisbon disaster and the 9/11 terrorist(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) attacks appeared impossible before they came to be. Yet the very fact that they happened meant that(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)they were possible; but their being possible also meant that they might not have happened. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)Their very singularity (real) combined with their potentiality (possible) means that terrorist acts and terrible acts of nature realise two temporalities simultaneously:(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;background: lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;background:lime;mso-highlight:lime&amp;#34; %)they constitute at once the actual and the possible, oscillating mesmerically between the poles of being and coming to be(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %). In the eighteenth century, Denis Diderot had already remarked on this particularity of terrible events when contemplating the sublime tableaux of natural catastrophes. He writes that(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) the human figures in these paintings alone inhabit two timeframes simultaneously, living at once their everyday routine and the singularity of the terrible event that befalls them (Diderot,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) 1984: 386). Henri Bergson in turn attributed the dual temporality of the terrible event not to its imagined victims but to its imaginative creators. It is the artist, he writes, who ‘crée du possible en même temps que du réel quand il exécute son oeuvre’ (1934: 130−1). It is a small step from there to Baudrillard’s assertion that artists are thus terrorists and vice versa, since(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) both conspire in the creation of singularities – that which erupts as event, and which resists(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) any of the ruling system’s various devices of assimilation, be they universalist (Enlightenment rights) or globalising (generalised exchange and commodification) (Baudrillard, 2002b: 74−5).7 The true artist, just like the true terrorist, refuses to enter into systems of exchange. As(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) a result, it is the fate of both terrorist and writer to fail. But they dare to fail, as Beckett said(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt; line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) of the modernist artist, ‘as no other dare fail, that failure is their world’ (1965: 125). For(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) failure, like geological fault-lines, is the unavowed structuring principle of the globalised(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %) world – (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)although no one thanks the artist or the terrorist for revealing this to us any more than(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 6pt; line-height: 115%; &amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %)we thank the earthquake for reminding us of plate tectonics(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%&amp;#34; %).

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

=== Extend the Baudrillard 93 ev; it says that money functions independently of its own aims. It is no longer a question of this computer is worth this much in gold, guaranteed by the value of the dolar, it is just speculation. Money doesn&amp;#39;t ground commodities to a common denominator for exchange, it has proliferated the exchange value of commodities. ===

